  <section|Introduction>

  In this paper we develop a Riemann-Hilbert approach to the theory of
  skew-orthogonal polynomials of symplectic type. In order to motivate our
  work let us recall the basic theory of orthogonal polynomials. One begins
  with a measurable function <math|w:\<bbb-R\>\<to\><around|[|0,+\<infty\>|)>>
  with finite moments to all orders, that is
  <math|<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>><around|\||x|\|><rsup|k>*w<around|(|x|)>*<space|0.17em>d*x\<less\>+\<infty\>>
  for all <math|k\<in\>\<bbb-N\>>. Then one constructs a Hermitian form

  <\equation*>
    <around|\<langle\>|P,Q|\<rangle\>><rsub|2>=<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>P<around|(|x|)>*Q<around|(|x|)>*w<around|(|x|)>*<space|0.17em>d*x
  </equation*>

  for (real) polynomials <math|P> and <math|Q>. We would like that
  <math|<around|\<langle\>|\<cdummy\>,\<cdummy\>|\<rangle\>><rsub|2>> be
  nondegenerate on the linear space of real polynomials so that we can make
  it into an inner product, which would be true if <math|w> is continuous and
  has positive mass <math|<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>w*<space|0.17em>d*x\<gtr\>0>.
  Given such an inner product there is a unique sequence of polynomials
  <math|<around|{|P<rsub|n>|}><rsub|n\<in\>\<bbb-N\>>> such that
  <math|P<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>=x<rsup|n>+\<cal-O\><around|(|x<rsup|n-1>|)>>
  and <math|<around|\<langle\>|P<rsub|n>,P<rsub|m>|\<rangle\>><rsub|2>=0> for
  <math|n\<neq\>m>, constructable by a Gram-Schmidt procedure. <math|w> is
  referred to as the <with|font-shape|italic|weight function> and
  <math|P<rsub|n>> is called the <math|n>th monic orthogonal polynomial with
  respect to <math|w>.

  The applications of orthogonal polynomials are extremely diverse, however
  in this work we shall be interested solely in their application to
  <with|font-shape|italic|random matrix theory> (see e.g. <cite|deiftbook>).
  Let <math|M> be an <math|n\<times\>n> Hermitian random matrix distributed
  according to a probability measure

  <\equation>
    <label|probmeas><frac|1|Z<rsub|n>>*e<rsup|-<math-up|tr><space|0.17em>V<around|(|M|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*M
  </equation>

  where <math|d*M=<big|prod><rsub|k=1><rsup|n>d*M<rsub|k*k>*<big|prod><rsub|1\<leq\>i\<less\>j\<leq\>n>d*\<Re\>*M<rsub|i*j>*d*\<Im\>*M<rsub|i*j>>,
  <math|V> is a real-valued analytic function on <math|\<bbb-R\>> and
  <math|Z<rsub|n>\<gtr\>0> is a constant of normalisation. For this measure
  to be normalisable <math|V<around|(|x|)>\<to\>+\<infty\>> as
  <math|x\<to\>\<pm\>\<infty\>> sufficiently rapidly, more precisely,
  <math|liminf<rsub|x\<to\>\<pm\>\<infty\>> <frac|V<around|(|x|)>|log
  <around|\||x|\|>>=+\<infty\>>. This condition would be satisfied if
  <math|V> was a polynomial of even degree and positive leading coefficient,
  as will be the case in this paper.

  A remarkable calculation (see Ch. 5 of <cite|mehta> or Ch. 5 of
  <cite|loggases>) then shows that the correlation functions of the
  eigenvalues of such an ensemble are expressible entirely in terms of the
  orthogonal polynomials <math|P<rsub|n>> and <math|P<rsub|n-1>> and their
  respective norms, <math|<around|\<\|\|\>|P<rsub|n>|\<\|\|\>>> and
  <math|<around|\<\|\|\>|P<rsub|n-1>|\<\|\|\>>>, with respect to the weight
  function <math|w<around|(|x|)>=e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>>. Thus to make an
  asymptotic analysis of the correlation functions as <math|n\<to\>\<infty\>>
  it is necessary to make an asymptotic analysis of orthogonal polynomials
  with respect to more or less arbitrary weight functions. For certain
  <enquote|classical> weight functions this can be done by classical steepest
  descent techniques, however the general case required the discovery of a
  <with|font-shape|italic|Riemann-Hilbert> representation of orthogonal
  polynomials <cite|fokas> and the development of the
  <with|font-shape|italic|nonlinear steepest descent> technique
  <cite|10.2307/2946540>. A Riemann-Hilbert representation involves
  representing an object of interest in terms of the solution to a boundary
  value problem in the complex plane with prescribed behaviour at infinity,
  and can be regarded as a generalisation of the notion of a contour integral
  <cite|itsRH>. This led to a proof of universality of local correlations in
  the bulk and at the edge of the spectrum for ensembles of type
  (<reference|probmeas>) by means of the so-called
  Deift-McLaughlin-Kriecherbauer-Venakides-Zhou (DMKVZ) scheme
  <cite|deift|deift2|deift3>, building off earlier work of Pastur-Shcherbina
  <cite|Pastur:1997aa> and Bleher-Its <cite|Its>.

  Motivated by, amongst others, applications to quantum mechanical systems
  with time-reversal invariance (see Ch. 2 of <cite|mehta>), random matrix
  theorists have also been interested for a long time in studying not only
  Hermitian but also real symmetric and quaternion self-dual random matrices
  with probability measures of the form of (<reference|probmeas>). These
  three cases, real symmetric, complex Hermitian and quaternion self-dual,
  correspond to the three finite-dimensional, associative division algebras
  over the real numbers, <math|\<bbb-R\>>, <math|\<bbb-C\>> and
  <math|\<bbb-H\>> respectively <cite|Dyson3>. These are often labelled by
  the <enquote|Dyson index> <math|\<beta\>=1,2,4> respectively.

  In this work we shall be interested in the case of <math|\<beta\>=4>, the
  so-called symplectic case, since the probability measure is invariant under
  conjugation by elements of the compact symplectic group, and since we
  prefer to think of an <math|n\<times\>n> quaternion matrix as a
  <math|2*n\<times\>2*n> matrix where the quaternions are represented by
  <math|2\<times\>2> blocks. For such a <math|2*n\<times\>2*n> matrix there
  are, with probability 1, only <math|n> distinct eigenvalues since every
  eigenvalue occurs with multiplicity <math|2> (known in the physics
  literature as Kramers' degeneracy). These <math|n> eigenvalues have the
  joint PDF

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|\<rho\><rsub|n><around|(|x<rsub|1>,\<ldots\>,x<rsub|n>|)>=<frac|1|<wide|Z|~><rsub|n>>*<big|prod><rsub|1\<leq\>i\<less\>j\<leq\>n><around|\||x<rsub|i>-x<rsub|j>|\|><rsup|4>*<big|prod><rsub|k=1><rsup|n>e<rsup|-2*V<around|(|x<rsub|k>|)>><eq-number><label|pointprocess>>>>>
  </align>

  where <math|<wide|Z|~><rsub|n>> is a normalisation constant. We shall
  furthermore restrict to the case of <math|V> being a real polynomial of
  even degree <math|D> and leading coefficient <math|\<gamma\>\<gtr\>0>

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|V<around|(|x|)>=\<gamma\>*x<rsup|D>+\<cal-O\><around|(|x<rsup|D-1>|)><eq-number>>>>>
  </align>

  Here the classical approach (see Ch. 5 of <cite|mehta>, Ch. 6 of
  <cite|loggases>) involves finding an analogue of orthogonal polynomials and
  this is supplied by <with|font-shape|italic|skew-orthogonal polynomials>.
  Here the inner product <math|<around|\<langle\>|\<cdummy\>,\<cdummy\>|\<rangle\>><rsub|2>>
  is replaced by a skew-symmetric nondegenerate bilinear form
  <math|<around|\<langle\>|\<cdummy\>,\<cdummy\>|\<rangle\>><rsub|4>>, where

  <\equation>
    <label|skewprod><around|\<langle\>|P,Q|\<rangle\>><rsub|4>=<frac|1|2>*<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>><around*|(|P<around|(|x|)>*Q<rprime|'><around|(|x|)>-P<rprime|'><around|(|x|)>*Q<around|(|x|)>|)>*e<rsup|-2*V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x
  </equation>

  for <math|P> and <math|Q> real polynomials. By <enquote|non-degenerate> we
  mean the following. Let <math|<with|math-font|cal*|P><rsub|k><rsup|\<bbb-R\>>>
  be the space of real polynomials of degree <math|\<leq\>k>. Then we say
  <math|<around|\<langle\>|\<cdummy\>,\<cdummy\>|\<rangle\>><rsub|4>> is
  non-degenerate if for all <math|n\<in\>\<bbb-N\>>, we have the implication

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|\<forall\>P\<in\><with|math-font|cal*|P><rsub|2*n+1><rsup|\<bbb-R\>>*<space|0.17em><space|0.17em><around*|(|<around|\<langle\>|P,Q|\<rangle\>><rsub|4>=0<space|1em>\<forall\>Q\<in\><with|math-font|cal*|P><rsub|2*n+1><rsup|\<bbb-R\>>|\<nobracket\>>>|<cell|>|<cell|\<Longrightarrow\>>|<cell|>|<cell|<around*|\<nobracket\>|P=0|)>>>>>
  </align*>

  Then a sequence of monic polynomials <math|<around|{|P<rsub|n>|}><rsub|n\<in\>\<bbb-N\>>>,
  <math|P<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>=x<rsup|n>+\<cal-O\><around|(|x<rsup|n-1>|)>>,
  is said to be skew-orthogonal with respect to
  <math|<around|\<langle\>|\<cdummy\>,\<cdummy\>|\<rangle\>><rsub|4>> if the
  following holds.

  <\enumerate>
    <item><math|<around|\<langle\>|P<rsub|2*n>,P<rsub|2*m>|\<rangle\>><rsub|4>=<around|\<langle\>|P<rsub|2*n+1>,P<rsub|2*m+1>|\<rangle\>><rsub|4>=0>
    for all <math|n,m\<in\>\<bbb-N\>>.

    <item><math|<around|\<langle\>|P<rsub|2*n>,P<rsub|2*m+1>|\<rangle\>><rsub|4>=0>
    for all <math|n,m\<in\>\<bbb-N\>>, <math|n\<neq\>m>.
  </enumerate>

  The existence of such a sequence is guaranteed by non-degeneracy (it can be
  constructed by a procedure analogous to Gram-Schmidt), however these
  properties do not uniquely define the sequence because one can replace
  <math|P<rsub|2*n+1>\<mapsto\>P<rsub|2*n+1>+\<alpha\>*P<rsub|2*n>> for any
  constant <math|\<alpha\>\<in\>\<bbb-R\>>. This degree of freedom may be
  fixed by demanding that the next-to-leading coefficient of
  <math|P<rsub|2*n+1>> is equal to a specified value (it is common to choose
  this value to be zero however this will not be the most convenient choice
  for us). It can then be verified that with this extra constraint the
  sequence is unique.

  The importance of skew-orthogonal polynomials for random matrix theory can
  be seen by the following. Let <math|h<rsub|n>=<around|\<langle\>|P<rsub|2*n>,P<rsub|2*n+1>|\<rangle\>><rsub|4>>
  be the <enquote|skew norm.> Then (see Prop. 6.1.6 and Prop. 6.1.7 of
  <cite|loggases>) all eigenvalue correlation functions associated to the
  point process (<reference|pointprocess>) may be expressed in terms of the
  so-called <with|font-shape|italic|pre-kernel>

  <\equation>
    <label|prekernel>S<rsub|n><around|(|x,y|)>=<big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n-1><frac|P<rsub|2*k><around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<frac|d|d*y>*<around*|(|P<rsub|2*k+1><around|(|y|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|y|)>>|)>-P<rsub|2*k+1><around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<frac|d|d*y>*<around*|(|P<rsub|2*k><around|(|y|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|y|)>>|)>|2*h<rsub|k>>
  </equation>

  Precisely, from <math|S<rsub|n>> one constructs a <math|2\<times\>2> matrix
  <enquote|kernel>, and then the <math|k>-point correlation function of the
  ensemble is written as a <math|2*k\<times\>2*k> Pfaffian, or equivalently,
  quaternion determinant (see Ch. 6 of <cite|loggases>). In particular, the
  1-point correlation function <math|R<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|x|)>=S<rsub|n><around|(|x,x|)>>.
  A similar treatment in terms of skew-orthogonal polynomials, though with a
  different skew-inner product than (<reference|skewprod>), can be done in
  the case of real symmetric matrices (<math|\<beta\>=1>).

  The importance of understanding skew-orthogonal polynomials of real and
  symplectic type (<math|\<beta\>=1,4>) was stressed by Dyson <cite|Dyson>
  when he wrote

  <\quote-env|W>
    e need to develop the theory of skew-orthogonal polynomials until it
    becomes a working tool as handy as the existing theory of orthogonal
    polynomials.
  </quote-env>

  Unfortunately this theory remains comparatively underdeveloped relative to
  that of orthogonal polynomials (<math|\<beta\>=2>). Nevertheless let us
  state some known results. Adler, Horozov and van Moerbeke
  <cite|Adler1999ThePL> give Pfaffian formulć for the even and odd
  skew-orthogonal polynomials for <math|\<beta\>=1,4>. Eynard
  <cite|Eynard:2001aa> derives Heine-type multiple integral formulć for even
  and odd skew-orthogonal polynomials for <math|\<beta\>=1,4> and he uses a
  non-rigorous but intriguing resolvent method to obtain
  <math|n\<to\>\<infty\>> asymptotics for the case of a one-cut polynomial
  potential. These multiple-integral formulć are morally equivalent to the
  Pfaffian formulć since the two may be related by de Bruijn identities
  <cite|debruijn>. In the case of <math|V<rprime|'>> being rational, Adler
  and van Moerbeke <cite|adler1999pfaff> find a natural basis of orthogonal
  polynomials in which to express the corresponding skew-orthogonal
  polynomials and Adler, Forrester, Nagao and van Moerbeke
  <cite|Adler:2000aa> use this to write simple expressions for the
  skew-orthogonal polynomials in the classical (Hermite, Laguerre and Jacobi)
  cases. A key inspiration for the present paper is the paper of Pierce
  <cite|PIERCE2008230> in which a Riemann-Hilbert representation for
  skew-orthogonal polynomials of real type (<math|\<beta\>=1>) with a
  polynomial <math|V> is derived; unfortunately this work has not received
  nearly the same attention as the corresponding problem for orthogonal
  polynomials because there is no known Christoffel-Darboux-type formula to
  express the pre-kernel in terms of the Riemann-Hilbert problem, and even if
  there was, the complexity of the jump matrix makes it unclear how to
  perform a nonlinear steepest descent analysis.

  The difficulty of working with skew-orthogonal polynomials has led some to
  believe that they are the wrong way to approach <math|\<beta\>=1,4>
  ensembles and to develop a different formalism that avoids skew-orthogonal
  polynomials entirely. This is the Widom formalism <cite|Widom:1999aa>,
  presented and developed in the excellent book of Deift and Gioev
  <cite|deiftuniversality>, and it is this formalism that has yielded proofs
  of universality of local correlations for <math|\<beta\>=1,4>
  <cite|Stojanovic:2000aa|Deift:2007aa|Shcherbina:2009aa|Shcherbina:2009ab|kriecherbauer2010fluctuations|Shcherbina:2011aa>.
  One of the aims of this paper is to show that an approach involving
  skew-orthogonal polynomials can nevertheless be highly fruitful.

  Let us now state our results. Given the sequence of skew-orthogonal
  polynomials <math|<around|{|P<rsub|n>|}><rsub|n\<in\>\<bbb-N\>>> we define
  the <enquote|dual> polynomials as <math|\<Psi\><rsub|n><around|(|x|)>=-<frac|1|\<gamma\>*D>*e<rsup|V<around|(|x|)>>*<frac|d|d*x>*<around*|(|P<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>|)>>.

  <\enumerate>
    <item>In Section <reference|rhpsection> we show how
    <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n>> and <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n+1>> may be thought of
    as <enquote|multiple-orthogonal polynomials of Type II> (Corollary
    <reference|typeII>). This yields two families of Riemann-Hilbert problems
    <math|A<rsub|n>> (<reference|evenrhp>) and <math|B<rsub|n>>
    (<reference|oddrhp>), where <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n>> and
    <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n+1>> appear as the <math|<around|(|1,1|)>> matrix
    element of <math|A<rsub|n>> and <math|B<rsub|n>> respectively.
    <math|A<rsub|n>> has dimension <math|D+1> and <math|B<rsub|n>> has
    dimension <math|D+2>. Furthermore, we find that <math|P<rsub|2*n>> is the
    <math|<around|(|2,2|)>> matrix element of <math|A<rsub|n><rsup|-1>>,
    however, somewhat contrary to what one might expect, neither
    <math|P<rsub|2*n+1>> nor any multiple of it appears as a matrix element
    of <math|B<rsub|n><rsup|-1>>. This seems to be related to the fact that
    <math|P<rsub|2*n>> can be thought of as a multiple-orthogonal polynomial
    of Type I (Corollary <reference|typeI>), but we are not aware of a way to
    represent <math|P<rsub|2*n+1>> in such a way.

    <item>In Section <reference|christoffelsection> we prove an analogue of
    the Christoffel-Darboux formula, namely

    <\equation>
      <boxed|S<rsub|n><around|(|x,y|)>=-<frac|1|4*\<pi\>*i>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>-V<around|(|y|)>>*<frac|<around*|(|A<rsub|n><rsup|-1><around|(|x|)>*A<rsub|n><around|(|y|)>|)><rsub|21>|x-y>>
    </equation>

    where <math|S<rsub|n>> is the pre-kernel (<reference|prekernel>) and
    <math|A<rsub|n>> is the solution of RHP <reference|evenrhp>. If a
    nonlinear steepest descent analysis could be carried out for
    <math|A<rsub|n>> we would thus obtain a new proof of universality for
    <math|\<beta\>=4>. It is also interesting to remark that the pre-kernel
    is expressible entirely in terms of the <enquote|even> Riemann-Hilbert
    problem <math|A<rsub|n>>, i.e. from the point of view of random matrix
    theory the odd problem <math|B<rsub|n>> can be ignored.

    <item>In Section <reference|dynamicsection> we show how the
    <math|A<rsub|n>> problem may be transformed to have constant jump
    matrices. Then allowing the potential <math|V> to depend on a parameter
    <math|t\<in\>\<bbb-R\>> by <math|V<around|(|z,t|)>=V<rsub|0><around|(|z|)>+z*t>,
    we derive an <math|<around|(|n,t|)>> Lax pair. The linear system in
    <math|n> could be regarded as a <math|\<beta\>=4> analogue of the
    <enquote|three term recurrence> which appears in the theory of orthogonal
    polynomials (Remark <reference|recurrence>). The compatibility condition
    of this Lax pair yields a dynamical system which one could regard as a
    <math|\<beta\>=4> analogue of the Toda lattice (Theorem
    <reference|skewtoda>). In the <math|D=2> case an exact solution can be
    given (Example <reference|exactsolution>). We should remark that an
    analogue of the Toda lattice for <math|\<beta\>=1,4>, with connections to
    skew-orthogonal polynomials, already exists in the literature under the
    name of the <enquote|Pfaff lattice> <cite|Adler1999ThePL>. The
    relationship between the Pfaff lattice and our dynamical system is left
    as a topic for future investigation.
  </enumerate>

  <new-page>

  <subsection|Notation>

  <\enumerate>
    <item>We shall use the notation <math|<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|k>> to
    stand for the rational function

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|k><around|(|x|)>=x<rsup|k>,>|<cell|>|<cell|k\<in\>\<bbb-Z\>.>>>>
    </align*>

    <item>For <math|k\<in\>\<bbb-N\>> define the space of real polynomials of
    degree at most <math|k> as

    <\equation*>
      <with|math-font|cal*|P><rsub|k><rsup|\<bbb-R\>>=<math-up|span><rsub|\<bbb-R\>><around|{|<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|0>,<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|1>,\<ldots\>,<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|k>|}>
    </equation*>

    and let

    <\equation*>
      <with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-R\>>=<big|cup><rsub|k=0><rsup|\<infty\>><with|math-font|cal*|P><rsub|k><rsup|\<bbb-R\>>
    </equation*>

    be the space of all real polynomials. Similarly, let
    <math|<with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>><rsub|k>> be the space of
    polynomials with complex coefficients of degree <math|\<leq\>k> and
    <math|<with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>>=\<cup\><rsub|k\<geq\>0><with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>><rsub|k>>.

    <item>For <math|m> a positive integer and <math|\<bbb-F\>> a field (in
    our case always <math|\<bbb-R\>> or <math|\<bbb-C\>>) we let
    <math|\<cal-M\><rsub|m><around|(|\<bbb-F\>|)>> be the space of
    <math|m\<times\>m> matrices with entries in <math|\<bbb-F\>>.

    <item>We use the convention that <math|0\<in\>\<bbb-N\>>.

    <item>We denote the 1-torus as <math|\<bbb-T\>=<around|{|z\<in\>\<bbb-C\><space|0.17em>:<space|0.17em><around|\||z|\|>=1|}>>.

    <item>We let <math|\<chi\><rsub|A>> be the indicator function of the set
    <math|A>, i.e. <math|\<chi\><rsub|A><around|(|x|)>=1> if <math|x\<in\>A>
    and <math|\<chi\><rsub|A><around|(|x|)>=0> otherwise.

    <item>Let <math|\<Gamma\>\<subset\>\<bbb-C\>> be a locally rectifiable
    contour in <math|\<bbb-C\>>. Then the <with|font-shape|italic|Cauchy
    transform> of the measurable function <math|f:\<Gamma\>\<to\>\<bbb-C\>>
    is defined as

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\>><around|(|f|)><around|(|z|)>=<frac|1|2*\<pi\>*i>*<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\>><frac|f<around|(|x|)>|x-z>*<space|0.17em>d*x>|<cell|>|<cell|z\<in\>\<bbb-C\>\<setminus\>\<Gamma\>>>>>
    </align*>

    whenever this integral exists. In our case we will always consider
    sufficiently <enquote|nice> functions <math|f> and contours
    <math|\<Gamma\>> such that the Cauchy transform is well-defined and
    analytic for all <math|z\<in\>\<bbb-C\>\<setminus\>\<Gamma\>>.
    Furthermore, we shall always consider functions with finite moments
    <math|<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\>><around|\||x|\|><rsup|k><around|\||f<around|(|x|)>|\|>*<space|0.17em><around|\||d*x|\|>\<less\>+\<infty\>>
    for all <math|k\<geq\>0> and for which
    <math|C<rsub|\<Gamma\>><around|(|f|)>> admits the asymptotic expansion in
    the sense of Poincaré

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\>><around|(|f|)><around|(|z|)>\<sim\>-<frac|1|2*\<pi\>*i>*<big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|\<infty\>>z<rsup|-k-1>*<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\>>x<rsup|k>*f<around|(|x|)>*<space|0.17em>d*x>|<cell|>|<cell|<around|(|z\<to\>\<infty\>|)>>>>>
    </align*>

    More precisely, for every <math|K\<in\>\<bbb-N\>> we have

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\>><around|(|f|)><around|(|z|)>=-<frac|1|2*\<pi\>*i>*<big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|K>z<rsup|-k-1>*<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\>>x<rsup|k>*f<around|(|x|)>*<space|0.17em>d*x+<frac|z<rsup|-K-1>|2*\<pi\>*i>*<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\>><frac|x<rsup|K+1>*f<around|(|x|)>|x-z>*<space|0.17em>d*x>>>>
    </align*>

    If <math|<math-up|dist><around|(|z,\<Gamma\>|)>\<geq\>\<epsilon\>\<gtr\>0>
    we find that <math|<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\>><frac|x<rsup|K+1>*f<around|(|x|)>|x-z>*<space|0.17em>d*x>
    is bounded. However if <math|f> is analytic we may deform the contour to
    achieve boundedness in a full neighbourhood of (complex) infinity. This
    will be the case in all the Cauchy integrals that appear in this paper.
    The general theory of such Cauchy integrals for functions of varying
    degrees of decay and regularity is discussed in notes of Deift
    <cite|deift2019riemannhilbert> and the book of Muskhelishvilli
    <cite|singular>.
  </enumerate>

  <new-page>

  <section|Riemann-Hilbert representations><label|rhpsection>

  Before proceeding let us demonstrate that the problem we are considering is
  well-posed. The following proposition is of course known to experts and is
  implicit in the discussion of skew-orthogonal polynomials found in
  textbooks, however we could not find an explicit statement of it and so we
  record it here.

  <\proposition>
    The skew-symmetric bilinear form defined by (<reference|skewprod>) is
    non-degenerate. Furthermore the skew-norms are all positive, i.e.
    <math|h<rsub|n>=<around|\<langle\>|P<rsub|2*n>,P<rsub|2*n+1>|\<rangle\>><rsub|4>\<gtr\>0>,
    for all <math|n\<geq\>0>.
  </proposition>

  <\proof>
    To demonstrate both claims it is sufficient to demonstrate that

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<math-up|pf><around*|(|<around|\<langle\>|<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|i-1>,<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|j-1>|\<rangle\>><rsub|4>|)><rsub|i,j=1><rsup|2*n>\<gtr\>0>|<cell|>|<cell|\<forall\>n\<geq\>1<text|>>>>>
    </align*>

    where <math|<math-up|pf>> is the Pfaffian. This follows from one of de
    Bruijn's identities <cite|debruijn>.

    <\equation*>
      <math-up|pf><around*|(|<around|\<langle\>|<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|i-1>,<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|j-1>|\<rangle\>><rsub|4>|)><rsub|i,j=1><rsup|2*n>=<frac|1|n!>*<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\><rsup|n>><big|prod><rsub|1\<leq\>i\<less\>j\<leq\>n><around|\||x<rsub|i>-x<rsub|j>|\|><rsup|4>*<big|prod><rsub|k=1><rsup|n>e<rsup|-2*V<around|(|x<rsub|k>|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x<rsub|1>*\<ldots\>*d*x<rsub|n>\<gtr\>0
    </equation*>
  </proof>

  We begin by observing that the symplectic inner product
  (<reference|skewprod>) can be re-written

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around|\<langle\>|P,Q|\<rangle\>><rsub|4>=<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>P<around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<frac|d|d*x>*<around*|(|Q<around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>|)>*<space|0.17em>d*x<eq-number>>>>>
  </align>

  <\definition>
    [Dual skew-orthogonal polynomials] Given a sequence of skew-orthogonal
    polynomials <math|<around|{|P<rsub|n>|}><rsub|n\<in\>\<bbb-N\>>> let us
    introduce the sequence of <enquote|dual> polynomials
    <math|<around|{|\<Psi\><rsub|n>|}><rsub|n\<in\>\<bbb-N\>>> where

    <\align>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|\<Psi\><rsub|n><around|(|x|)>\<assign\>-<frac|1|\<gamma\>*D>*e<rsup|V<around|(|x|)>>*<frac|d|d*x>*<around*|(|e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*P<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>|)>=x<rsup|n+D-1>+\<cal-O\><around|(|x<rsup|n+D-2>|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|<around|(|x\<to\>\<infty\>|)><eq-number><label|dual>>>>>
    </align>
  </definition>

  The monic skew-orthogonal polynomials can be reconstructed from the dual
  polynomials by integration.

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|P<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>=\<gamma\>*D*e<rsup|V<around|(|x|)>>*<big|int><rsub|x><rsup|+\<infty\>>e<rsup|-V<around|(|y|)>>*\<Psi\><rsub|n><around|(|y|)>*<space|0.17em>d*y<eq-number>>>>>
  </align>

  In order to characterise <math|\<Psi\><rsub|n>> let us ask the following
  question. Given a polynomial <math|Q\<in\><with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>>>,
  under what conditions will

  <\equation*>
    e<rsup|V<around|(|x|)>>*<big|int><rsub|x><rsup|+\<infty\>>e<rsup|-V<around|(|y|)>>*Q<around|(|y|)>*<space|0.17em>d*y
  </equation*>

  also be a polynomial? Note that this is equivalent to the question of
  whether <math|Q> can be written <math|Q<around|(|x|)>=e<rsup|V<around|(|x|)>>*<frac|d|d*x>*<around*|(|P<around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>|)>>
  for some polynomial <math|P>. Let us now proceed to answer this question.

  <\remark>
    <label|polyunique>Note that the map <math|P\<mapsto\>e<rsup|V>*<frac|d|d*x>*<around|(|P*e<rsup|-V>|)>>
    which maps <math|<with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>>\<to\><with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>>>
    is linear and injective. Thus if <math|Q=e<rsup|V>*<frac|d|d*x>*<around|(|P*e<rsup|-V>|)>>
    then this <math|P> is unique.
  </remark>

  Consider the contours

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|C<rsub|k>=e<rsup|2*\<pi\>*i*<frac|k|D>>*<around|[|0,+\<infty\>|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|k=0,\<ldots\>,D-1<eq-number><label|contour1>>>>>
  </align>

  Let us orient these contours so <math|C<rsub|0>=<around|[|0,+\<infty\>|)>>
  has left to right orientation, whereas the remaining contours
  <math|C<rsub|1>,\<ldots\>,C<rsub|D-1>> have orientation towards the origin.
  Then let

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|\<Gamma\><rsub|k>=C<rsub|0>\<cup\>C<rsub|k>>|<cell|>|<cell|k=1,\<ldots\>,D-1<eq-number><label|contour2>>>>>
  </align>

  For example, when <math|k=<frac|D|2>> (recall <math|D> is even and
  positive), <math|\<Gamma\><rsub|k>=\<bbb-R\>> with standard left to right
  orientation. These contours are depicted in Figure <reference|contours> for
  the case <math|D=8>.

  <\big-figure>
    <\padded-center>
      <\picture-mixed|<image|<tuple|<#>|eps>|194pt|194pt||>>
        \\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]

        \t\t\\draw[blue, thick,-\<gtr\>] (0,0) -- (2,0);

        \t\t\\draw[blue, thick] (0,0) -- (4,0);

        \t\t\\draw[blue, thick] (2,0) -- node[below] {$C_0$}(4,0);

        \t\t\\draw[blue,thick,-\<gtr\>] (0,4) -- node[right] {$C_2$}(0,2);

        \t\t\\draw[blue, thick] (0,0) -- (0,4);

        \t\t\\draw[blue,thick] (0,0) -- (2*99/70,2*99/70);

        \t\t\\draw[blue,thick,-\<gtr\>] (2*99/70,2*99/70) -- node[right]
        {$C_1$} (99/70,99/70);

        \t\t\\draw[blue, thick] (0,0) -- (-4,0);

        \t\t\\draw[blue, thick,-\<gtr\>] (-4,0) -- node[below] {$C_4$}
        (-2,0);

        \t\t\\draw[blue,thick,-\<gtr\>] (0,-4) -- node[right] {$C_6$} (0,-2);

        \t\t\\draw[blue,thick] (0,0) -- (0,-4);

        \t\t\\draw[blue,thick] (0,0) -- (-2*99/70,-2*99/70);

        \t\t\\draw[blue, thick,-\<gtr\>] (-2*99/70,-2*99/70) -- node[right]
        {$C_5$} (-99/70,-99/70);

        \t\t\\draw[blue,thick] (0,0) -- (-2*99/70,2*99/70);

        \t\t\\draw[blue, thick,-\<gtr\>] (-2*99/70,2*99/70) -- node[left]
        {$C_3$} (-99/70,99/70);

        \t\t\\draw[blue, thick] (0,0) -- (2*99/70,-2*99/70);

        \t\t\\draw[blue, thick,-\<gtr\>] (2*99/70,-2*99/70) -- node[left]
        {$C_7$} (99/70,-99/70);

        \\end{tikzpicture}
      </picture-mixed>
    </padded-center>

    <label|contours>
  </big-figure|This figure depicts the contours
  <math|C<rsub|0>,\<ldots\>,C<rsub|D-1>> in the case <math|D=8>. The arrows
  denote the orientation of the contours. Note the outgoing orientation of
  <math|C<rsub|0>>.>

  <\proposition>
    <label|representation>Let <math|Q\<in\><with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>>>
    be a polynomial. <math|Q> can written as

    <\equation*>
      Q<around|(|x|)>=e<rsup|V<around|(|x|)>>*<frac|d|d*x>*<around*|(|e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*P<around|(|x|)>|)>
    </equation*>

    for some polynomial <math|P\<in\><with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>>>
    if and only if the following integrals vanish.

    <\align>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|k>>Q<around|(|z|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|z|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*z=0>|<cell|>|<cell|\<forall\>k=1,\<ldots\>,D-1<eq-number><label|integrals>>>>>
    </align>
  </proposition>

  <\proof>
    <enquote|Only if> is trivial since for
    <math|z\<in\>C<rsub|k>\<setminus\><around|{|0|}>>,
    <math|z<rsup|D>\<gtr\>0>, hence <math|P<around|(|z|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|z|)>>>
    is rapidly decreasing, hence

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|k>>Q<around|(|z|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|z|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*z=<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|k>><frac|d|d*z>*<around*|(|P<around|(|z|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|z|)>>|)>*<space|0.17em>d*z=0>|<cell|>|<cell|\<forall\>k=1,\<ldots\>,D-1>>>>
    </align*>

    For the converse claim, suppose the integrals (<reference|integrals>) all
    vanish. Let us then divide <math|D> into <math|deg Q+1> with remainder,
    so that <math|deg Q+1=D*\<ell\>+r> where <math|\<ell\>,r\<in\>\<bbb-N\>>
    and <math|r\<leq\>D-1>.

    We will construct a certain polynomial <math|R> as follows. If <math|deg
    Q\<leq\>D-2> then <math|R\<assign\>Q>, so we may assume <math|deg
    Q\<geq\>D-1>. We can then factorise

    <\equation*>
      Q<around|(|x|)>=F<rsub|1><around|(|x|)>*V<rprime|'><around|(|x|)>+G<rsub|1><around|(|x|)>
    </equation*>

    where <math|F<rsub|1>\<in\><with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>>> has
    degree <math|deg Q-D+1> and <math|G<rsub|1>\<in\><with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>>>
    has degree at most <math|D-2>. We can then repeat the procedure.

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|F<rsub|1><rprime|'><around|(|x|)>>|<cell|=F<rsub|2><around|(|x|)>*V<rprime|'><around|(|x|)>+G<rsub|2><around|(|x|)>>>|<row|<cell|F<rsub|2><rprime|'><around|(|x|)>>|<cell|=F<rsub|3><around|(|x|)>*V<rprime|'><around|(|x|)>+G<rsub|3><around|(|x|)>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|\<vdots\>>>|<row|<cell|F<rsub|\<ell\>-1><rprime|'><around|(|x|)>>|<cell|=F<rsub|\<ell\>><around|(|x|)>*V<rprime|'><around|(|x|)>+G<rsub|\<ell\>><around|(|x|)>>>>>
    </align*>

    <math|F<rsub|j>\<in\><with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>>> has degree
    <math|deg Q-D*j+1> and <math|G<rsub|j>\<in\><with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>>>
    has degree at most <math|D-2> for <math|j=1,\<ldots\>,\<ell\>>. In
    particular <math|F<rsub|\<ell\>>> has degree <math|r> and so the process
    terminates at this stage. Let

    <\equation*>
      R<around|(|x|)>\<assign\>G<rsub|1><around|(|x|)>+\<ldots\>+G<rsub|\<ell\>><around|(|x|)>+F<rsub|\<ell\>><rprime|'><around|(|x|)>
    </equation*>

    <math|R> has degree at most <math|D-2>.

    By repeated integration by parts we see that

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|k>>R<around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x=0>|<cell|>|<cell|\<forall\>k=1,\<ldots\>,D-1>>>>
    </align*>

    We now claim that <math|R\<equiv\>0>. Consider the function

    <\equation*>
      C<around|(|z|)>\<assign\>e<rsup|V<around|(|z|)>>*<big|int><rsub|z><rsup|+\<infty\>>R<around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x
    </equation*>

    where the integration path is from <math|z\<in\>\<bbb-C\>> to <math|0>
    then from <math|0> to <math|+\<infty\>>. <math|C> is clearly an entire
    function. We claim that as <math|<around|\||z|\|>\<to\>+\<infty\>>,
    <math|C<around|(|z|)>\<to\>0>, uniformly in
    <math|<math-up|arg><space|0.17em>z>. Hence by Liouville's theorem
    <math|C\<equiv\>0>, and hence <math|R\<equiv\>0>.

    From our assumptions

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<big|int><rsub|z><rsup|+\<infty\>>R<around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x=<big|int><rsub|z><rsup|<around|(|+\<infty\>|)>\<cdot\>e<rsup|2*\<pi\>*i*<frac|k|D>>>R<around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x>|<cell|>|<cell|\<forall\>k=1,\<ldots\>,D-1>>>>
    </align*>

    Now introduce the function <math|\<varphi\><around|(|z|)>=<wide|V|~><around|(|z|)><rsup|\<nosymbol\>>*1*D>
    (where <math|<wide|V|~><around|(|z|)>=<frac|1|\<gamma\>>*V<around|(|z|)>>)
    which is holomorphic and injective so long as <math|<around|\||z|\|>> is
    sufficiently large, i.e. on a neighbourhood of (complex) infinity. Let us
    choose <math|k\<in\><around|{|0,\<ldots\>,D-1|}>> so that
    <math|2*\<pi\>*<frac|k-<frac|1|2>|D>\<leq\>arg
    \<varphi\><around|(|z|)>\<leq\>2*\<pi\>*<frac|k+<frac|1|2>|D>> (this
    <math|k> may not be unique but this doesn't matter). Let us also define
    <math|arg> so that there is no branch cut through this sector. Finally,
    let us choose the contour such that <math|\<Re\>*V<around|(|z|)>> is
    always non-decreasing along the contour. The existence of such a contour
    is proven in Lemma <reference|contour>. Integrating by parts we find

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<big|int><rsub|z><rsup|<around|(|+\<infty\>|)>\<cdot\>e<rsup|2*\<pi\>*i*<frac|k|D>>>R<around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x=<frac|R<around|(|z|)>|V<rprime|'><around|(|z|)>>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|z|)>>+<big|int><rsub|z><rsup|<around|(|+\<infty\>|)>\<cdot\>e<rsup|2*\<pi\>*i*<frac|k|D>>><frac|d|d*x><around*|(|<frac|R<around|(|x|)>|V<rprime|'><around|(|x|)>>|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x>>>>
    </align*>

    <math|<frac|d|d*x><around*|(|<frac|R<around|(|x|)>|V<rprime|'><around|(|x|)>>|)>>
    is a rational function which scales like <math|x<rsup|-2>> and so for
    <math|<around|\||x|\|>> sufficiently large there is a constant
    <math|\<kappa\>\<gtr\>0> such that <math|<around*|\||<frac|d|d*x><around*|(|<frac|R<around|(|x|)>|V<rprime|'><around|(|x|)>>|)>|\|>\<leq\>\<kappa\><around|\||x|\|><rsup|-2>>.
    Thus

    <\equation*>
      <around*|\||e<rsup|V<around|(|z|)>>*<big|int><rsub|z><rsup|<around|(|+\<infty\>|)>\<cdot\>e<rsup|2*\<pi\>*i*<frac|k|D>>>R<around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x|\|>\<leq\><frac|<around|\||R<around|(|z|)>|\|>|<around|\||V<rprime|'><around|(|z|)>|\|>>+\<kappa\>*<big|int><rsub|z><rsup|<around|(|+\<infty\>|)>\<cdot\>e<rsup|2*\<pi\>*i*<frac|k|D>>><around|\||x|\|><rsup|-2>*<around|\||d*x|\|>\<to\>0
    </equation*>

    as <math|z\<to\>\<infty\>>. This limit holds so long as <math|z> is
    confined to the sector <math|2*\<pi\>*<frac|k-<frac|1|2>|D>\<leq\>arg
    \<varphi\><around|(|z|)>\<leq\>2*\<pi\>*<frac|k+<frac|1|2>|D>>, however
    since there are only finitely many such sectors this limit thus holds
    uniformly in <math|<math-up|arg><space|0.17em>\<varphi\><around|(|z|)>>
    (and so uniformly in <math|<math-up|arg><space|0.17em>z>). Thus
    <math|R\<equiv\>0>.

    Finally, this shows that <math|e<rsup|V<around|(|z|)>>*<big|int><rsub|z><rsup|+\<infty\>>Q<around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x>
    is a polynomial, since if we factorise <math|Q> and integrate by parts we
    find

    <\equation*>
      e<rsup|V<around|(|z|)>>*<big|int><rsub|z><rsup|+\<infty\>>Q<around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x=F<rsub|1><around|(|z|)>+\<ldots\>+F<rsub|\<ell\>><around|(|z|)>
    </equation*>

    which is a polynomial of degree <math|deg Q-D+1>.
  </proof>

  <\lemma>
    <label|contour>Let <math|<wide|V|~><around|(|w|)>=<frac|1|\<gamma\>>*V<around|(|w|)>=w<rsup|D>+\<cal-O\><around|(|w<rsup|D-1>|)>>
    and let <math|\<varphi\><around|(|w|)>\<assign\><wide|V|~><around|(|w|)><rsup|\<nosymbol\>>*1*D>.
    There exists a <math|\<varrho\>\<gtr\>0> sufficiently large such that
    <math|\<varphi\>> is analytic and injective on
    <math|U<rsub|\<varrho\>>\<assign\><around|{|z\<in\>\<bbb-C\><space|0.17em>:<space|0.17em><around|\||z|\|>\<gtr\>\<varrho\>|}>>
    and such that the following holds. For each
    <math|z\<in\>U<rsub|\<varrho\>>> such that
    <math|<frac|2*\<pi\>*<around|(|k-<frac|1|2>|)>|D>\<leq\>arg
    \<varphi\><around|(|z|)>\<leq\><frac|2*\<pi\>*<around|(|k+<frac|1|2>|)>|D>>
    there is a of contour <math|\<tau\><rsub|z>> starting at <math|z> and
    tending to <math|<around|(|+\<infty\>|)>\<cdot\>e<rsup|2*\<pi\>*i*<frac|k|D>>>
    such that <math|\<Re\>*V<around|(|w|)>> is non-decreasing along the
    contour and <math|<big|int><rsub|\<tau\><rsub|z>><around|\||x|\|><rsup|-2>*<around|\||d*x|\|>\<to\>0>
    as <math|<around|\||z|\|>\<to\>\<infty\>> uniformly in
    <math|<math-up|arg><space|0.17em>z>.
  </lemma>

  <\proof>
    Let

    <\equation*>
      <wide|\<tau\>|~><around|(|s|)>=<choice|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around|\||\<varphi\><around|(|z|)>|\|>*exp
      <around*|(|i*<around|(|1-s|)>*arg \<varphi\><around|(|z|)>+i*s<frac|2*\<pi\>*k|D>|)>>|<cell|s\<in\><around|[|0,1|]>>>|<row|<cell|<around|(|<around|\||\<varphi\><around|(|z|)>|\|>+s-1|)>*exp
      <around|(|i*<frac|2*\<pi\>*k|D>|)>>|<cell|s\<in\><around|[|1,\<infty\>|)>>>>>>
    </equation*>

    Then we choose our contour to be the preimage of <math|<wide|\<tau\>|~>>,
    that is <math|\<tau\>=\<varphi\><rsup|-1>\<circ\><wide|\<tau\>|~>>. From
    this we see that <math|V<around|(|\<tau\><around|(|s|)>|)>=\<gamma\>*<wide|\<tau\>|~><around|(|s|)><rsup|D>>.
    A short calculation then shows that for <math|s\<in\><around|(|0,1|)>>

    <\equation*>
      <frac|d|d*s>*\<Re\>*V<around|(|\<tau\><around|(|s|)>|)>=\<gamma\><around|\||\<varphi\><around|(|z|)>|\|><rsup|D>*D*<around*|(|arg
      \<varphi\><around|(|z|)>-<frac|2*\<pi\>*k|D>|)>*sin
      <around*|(|D*<around|(|1-s|)>*<around*|(|arg
      \<varphi\><around|(|z|)>-<frac|2*\<pi\>*k|D>|)>|)>\<geq\>0
    </equation*>

    It is also easy to show for <math|s\<in\><around|(|1,\<infty\>|)>>,
    <math|<frac|d|d*s>*\<Re\><wide|\<tau\>|~><around|(|s|)><rsup|D>\<geq\>0>.
    Furthermore <math|\<varphi\><around|(|w|)>=w*<around|(|1+o<around|(|1|)>|)>>
    and <math|\<varphi\><rprime|'><around|(|w|)>=1+o<around|(|1|)>> uniformly
    on <math|U<rsub|\<varrho\>>> as <math|\<varrho\>\<to\>+\<infty\>>, and so
    <math|<big|int><rsub|\<tau\>><around|\||x|\|><rsup|-2>*<around|\||d*x|\|>\<to\>0>
    as <math|<around|\||z|\|>\<to\>\<infty\>> uniformly in
    <math|<math-up|arg><space|0.17em>z>.
  </proof>

  <\proposition>
    <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n>> has at least <math|2*n+1> real zeros (not
    counting multiplicity), of which at least <math|2*n+2-<frac|D|2>> must be
    simple. <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n+1>> has at least <math|2*n> real zeros
    (not counting multiplicity), of which <math|2*n-<frac|D|2>> must be
    simple.
  </proposition>

  <\proof>
    Let <math|x<rsub|1>,\<ldots\>,x<rsub|\<ell\>>> be the collection of real
    zeros of <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n>> with odd multiplicity, i.e. exactly
    those points on <math|\<bbb-R\>> at which <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n>>
    changes sign, where we do not repeat according to multiplicity. Then
    <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n><around|(|x|)>*<around|(|x-x<rsub|1>|)>*\<ldots\>*<around|(|x-x<rsub|\<ell\>>|)>>
    has the same sign everywhere and vanishes only on a finite set, hence

    <\equation*>
      <big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>\<Psi\><rsub|2*n><around|(|x|)>*<around|(|x-x<rsub|1>|)>*\<ldots\>*<around|(|x-x<rsub|\<ell\>>|)>*e<rsup|-2*V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x\<neq\>0
    </equation*>

    However if <math|\<ell\>\<leq\>2*n> then the above integral vanishes,
    thus <math|\<ell\>\<geq\>2*n+1>. Furthermore it is easily seen that at
    least <math|2*n+2-<frac|D|2>> of these must be simple. A similar argument
    works for <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n+1>>.
  </proof>

  We now arrive at a pair of Riemann-Hilbert problems, for the even and odd
  dual skew-orthogonal polynomials respectively. In what follows, it is more
  convenient to ensure the uniqueness of the sequence by fixing the
  next-to-leading coefficient of <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n+1>> to be zero rather
  than <math|P<rsub|2*n+1>>. We begin with the <enquote|even problem,> so
  called because the <math|<around|(|1,1|)>> matrix element of the solution
  will turn out to be <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n>>.

  <\rhp>
    [Even problem]<label|evenrhp> Let <math|V> be a real polynomial of even
    degree <math|D\<geq\>2> and positive leading coefficient,
    <math|\<Gamma\><rsub|j>> be defined by (<reference|contour1>) and
    (<reference|contour2>), and

    <\equation>
      <label|gamma>\<Gamma\>=<big|cup><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<Gamma\><rsub|j>
    </equation>

    with the orientations of <math|\<Gamma\><rsub|j>> inherited by
    <math|\<Gamma\>> (see e.g. Figure <reference|contours>). We look for a
    <math|<around|(|D+1|)>\<times\><around|(|D+1|)>> matrix valued function

    <\equation*>
      A<rsub|n>:\<bbb-C\>\<setminus\>\<Gamma\>\<to\>\<cal-M\><rsub|D+1><around|(|\<bbb-C\>|)>
    </equation*>

    such that

    <\enumerate>
      <item><math|A<rsub|n>> is analytic on
      <math|\<bbb-C\>\<setminus\>\<Gamma\>> (that is, its matrix elements are
      analytic on <math|\<bbb-C\>\<setminus\>\<Gamma\>>).

      <item><math|A<rsub|n>> has continuous boundary values up to
      <math|\<Gamma\>\<setminus\><around|{|0|}>>. That is, given
      <math|x\<in\>\<Gamma\>\<setminus\><around|{|0|}>>, as
      <math|\<bbb-C\>\<setminus\>\<Gamma\>\<ni\>z\<to\>x> from either the
      <math|+> (left) side or <math|-> (right) side non-tangentially, the
      limit of <math|A<rsub|n><around|(|z|)>> exists. These limits are
      denoted

      <\align*>
        <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|A<rsub|n><rsup|+>:\<Gamma\>\<setminus\><around|{|0|}>\<to\>\<cal-M\><rsub|D+1><around|(|\<bbb-C\>|)>>>|<row|<cell|A<rsub|n><rsup|->:\<Gamma\>\<setminus\><around|{|0|}>\<to\>\<cal-M\><rsub|D+1><around|(|\<bbb-C\>|)>>>>>
      </align*>

      and are continuous functions. <enquote|Left> and <enquote|right> mean
      relative to the orientation of the contour.

      <item><math|A<rsub|n>> is bounded in a neighbourhood of <math|0>.

      <item>The boundary values are related by the <enquote|jump matrix>

      <\align>
        <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|A<rsub|n><rsup|+><around|(|x|)>=A<rsub|n><rsup|-><around|(|x|)><around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-lborder|0ln>|<cwith|1|-1|2|2|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|3|3|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|4|4|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|5|5|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|6|6|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|7|7|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|8|8|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|9|9|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|10|10|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|11|11|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|12|12|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|13|13|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|14|14|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|15|15|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|16|16|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|17|17|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|18|18|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|19|19|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|19|19|cell-rborder|0ln>|<table|<row|<cell|1<space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>e<rsup|-2*V>*\<chi\><rsub|\<bbb-R\>><space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>e<rsup|-V>*\<chi\><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>><space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>\<ldots\><space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>e<rsup|-V>*\<chi\><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|D-1>>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|1>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|1>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|\<ddots\>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|1>>>>>|)>,>|<cell|>|<cell|x\<in\>\<Gamma\>\<setminus\><around|{|0|}><eq-number>>>>>
      </align>

      <item>We have the normalisation

      <\align*>
        <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|A<rsub|n><around|(|z|)>=<around*|(|\<bbb-I\>+\<cal-O\><around|(|z<rsup|-1>|)>|)><around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|z<rsup|2*n+D-1>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|z<rsup|-2*n>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|z<rsup|-1>>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|\<ddots\>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|z<rsup|-1>>>>>>|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|<around|(|z\<to\>\<infty\>|)>>>>>
      </align*>
    </enumerate>
  </rhp>

  <\lemma>
    <label|uniqueness>If a solution to the Riemann-Hilbert problem
    (<reference|evenrhp>) exists, then it is unique.
  </lemma>

  <\proof>
    This method is standard but we repeat it for completeness. We note that
    the jump matrix has determinant <math|1> so <math|det
    A<rsub|n><around|(|z|)>> has no jump across
    <math|\<Gamma\>\<setminus\><around|{|0|}>> and takes continuous boundary
    values, so by Morera's theorem is analytic everywhere except possibly at
    <math|0>. However the requirement of boundedness in a neighbourhood of
    <math|0> implies that the singularity at <math|0> is removable. Hence
    <math|z\<mapsto\>det A<rsub|n><around|(|z|)>> is entire. Furthermore we
    have the normalisation

    <\equation*>
      det A<rsub|n><around|(|z|)>=1+\<cal-O\><around|(|z<rsup|-1>|)>,
    </equation*>

    as <math|z\<to\>\<infty\>> and so

    <\equation*>
      det A<rsub|n><around|(|z|)>\<equiv\>1
    </equation*>

    Then let <math|<wide|A|~><rsub|n>> be another solution. Then the function

    <\equation*>
      z\<mapsto\><wide|A|~><rsub|n><around|(|z|)>*A<rsub|n><rsup|-1><around|(|z|)>
    </equation*>

    has no jump across <math|\<Gamma\>\<setminus\><around|{|0|}>> and obtains
    continuous boundary values, so by Morera's theorem is analytic everywhere
    except possibly at <math|0>. Again by the requirement of boundedness in a
    neighbourhood of <math|0> we see that the singularity at <math|0> is
    removable. Hence <math|z\<mapsto\><wide|A|~><rsub|n><around|(|z|)>*A<rsub|n><rsup|-1><around|(|z|)>>
    is actually entire. Finally, since

    <\equation*>
      <wide|A|~><rsub|n><around|(|z|)>*A<rsub|n><rsup|-1><around|(|z|)>=\<bbb-I\>+\<cal-O\><around|(|z<rsup|-1>|)>
    </equation*>

    we find that <math|<wide|A|~><rsub|n><around|(|z|)>*A<rsub|n><rsup|-1><around|(|z|)>\<equiv\>\<bbb-I\>>.
  </proof>

  The jump condition implies that <math|<around|(|A<rsub|n>|)><rsub|11>> is
  an entire function which scales like <math|z<rsup|2*n+D-1>> as
  <math|z\<to\>\<infty\>>. It is therefore a monic polynomial of degree
  <math|2*n+D-1> by Liouville's theorem,

  <\equation*>
    <around|(|A<rsub|n>|)><rsub|11>\<assign\>Q\<in\><with|math-font|cal*|P><rsub|2*n+D-1><rsup|\<bbb-C\>>
  </equation*>

  The Plemelj formula then implies that the first row of <math|A<rsub|n>> is

  <\equation*>
    <around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-lborder|0ln>|<cwith|1|-1|2|2|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|3|3|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|4|4|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|5|5|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|6|6|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|7|7|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|8|8|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|9|9|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|10|10|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|11|11|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|12|12|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|13|13|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|13|13|cell-rborder|0ln>|<table|<row|<cell|Q>|<cell|<space|0.17em>,<space|0.17em>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<bbb-R\>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-2*V>*Q|)>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>,<space|0.17em>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*Q|)>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>,<space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>\<ldots\>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>,<space|0.17em>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|D-1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*Q|)>>>>>>|)>
  </equation*>

  From the asymptotic condition

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|j>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*Q|)><around|(|z|)>=\<cal-O\><around|(|z<rsup|-2>|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|\<forall\>j=1,\<ldots\>,D-1>>>>
  </align*>

  we see, by Proposition <reference|representation>, that there exists a
  unique <math|P\<in\><with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>>> of degree
  exactly <math|2*n> such that <math|Q=e<rsup|V>*<frac|d|d*x>*<around|(|P*e<rsup|-V>|)>>.
  Finally, the normalisation

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|C<rsub|\<bbb-R\>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-2*V>*Q|)><around|(|z|)>=\<cal-O\><around|(|z<rsup|-2*n-1>|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|<around|(|z\<to\>\<infty\>|)>>>>>
  </align*>

  implies that <math|<around|\<langle\>|<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|k>,P|\<rangle\>><rsub|4>=0>
  for <math|k=0,\<ldots\>,2*n-1>, and so <math|P> is skew-orthogonal. Thus
  <math|Q=\<Psi\><rsub|2*n>>.

  For the second row, we see that <math|<around|(|A<rsub|n>|)><rsub|21>\<assign\><wide|Q|~>>
  is a polynomial of degree at most <math|2*n+D-2>. Following the same
  procedure as above, we see that the second row is

  <\equation*>
    <around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-lborder|0ln>|<cwith|1|-1|2|2|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|3|3|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|4|4|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|5|5|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|6|6|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|7|7|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|8|8|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|9|9|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|10|10|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|11|11|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|12|12|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|13|13|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|13|13|cell-rborder|0ln>|<table|<row|<cell|<wide|Q|~>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>,<space|0.17em>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<bbb-R\>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-2*V>*<wide|Q|~>|)>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>,<space|0.17em>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*<wide|Q|~>|)>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>,<space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>\<ldots\>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>,<space|0.17em>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|D-1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*<wide|Q|~>|)>>>>>>|)>
  </equation*>

  where now <math|<wide|Q|~>=-<frac|2*\<pi\>*i*\<gamma\>*D|h<rsub|n-2>>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n-2>>.
  For the remaining rows, we see that <math|<around|(|A<rsub|n>|)><rsub|j+2,1>\<assign\>R<rsup|<around|(|j|)>><rsub|n>\<in\><with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>><rsub|2*n+D-2>>
  must be a polynomial of degree at most <math|2*n+D-2>. To show there exists
  a unique solution to RHP (<reference|evenrhp>), let us introduce the
  following linear functionals,

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|>|<cell|\<alpha\><rsub|j>:<with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>><rsub|2*n+D-2>\<to\>\<bbb-C\>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|\<beta\><rsub|j>:<with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>><rsub|2*n+D-2>\<to\>\<bbb-C\>>>>>
  </align*>

  where

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|\<alpha\><rsub|j><around|(|P|)>>|<cell|=<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>e<rsup|-2*V<around|(|x|)>>*x<rsup|j>*P<around|(|x|)>*<space|0.17em>d*x>|<cell|>|<cell|j=0,\<ldots\>,2*n-1<eq-number><label|alpha>>>|<row|<cell|\<beta\><rsub|j><around|(|P|)>>|<cell|=-<frac|1|2*\<pi\>*i>*<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|j>>e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*P<around|(|x|)>*<space|0.17em>d*x>|<cell|>|<cell|j=1,\<ldots\>,D-1<eq-number><label|beta>>>>>
  </align>

  <\lemma>
    <label|linindep><math|\<alpha\><rsub|0>,\<ldots\>,\<alpha\><rsub|2*n-1>,\<beta\><rsub|1>,\<ldots\>,\<beta\><rsub|D-1>>
    form a linearly independent set (and thus span
    <math|<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|P><rsub|2*n+D-2><rsup|\<bbb-C\>>|)><rsup|\<ast\>>>).
  </lemma>

  <\proof>
    To show this we need only show that

    <\equation*>
      <big|cap><rsub|j=0><rsup|2*n-1>ker \<alpha\><rsub|j>\<cap\><big|cap><rsub|k=1><rsup|D-1>ker
      \<beta\><rsub|k>=0
    </equation*>

    Thus let <math|Q\<in\><with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>><rsub|2*n+D-2>>
    be such that <math|\<alpha\><rsub|0><around|(|Q|)>=\<ldots\>=\<alpha\><rsub|2*n-1><around|(|Q|)>=\<beta\><rsub|1><around|(|Q|)>=\<ldots\>=\<beta\><rsub|D-1><around|(|Q|)>=0>.
    Thus by Proposition <reference|representation>,
    <math|Q=e<rsup|V>*<frac|d|d*x>*<around*|(|P*e<rsup|-V>|)>> for some
    <math|P\<in\><with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>><rsub|2*n-1>>.
    Furthermore <math|<around|\<langle\>|<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|0>,P|\<rangle\>><rsub|4>=\<ldots\>=<around|\<langle\>|<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|2*n-1>,P|\<rangle\>><rsub|4>=0>.
    Hence <math|P> is skew-orthogonal to all of
    <math|<with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>><rsub|2*n-1>>. Thus by the
    non-degeneracy of the inner product <math|<around|\<langle\>|\<cdummy\>,\<cdummy\>|\<rangle\>><rsub|4>>,
    <math|P\<equiv\>0> and hence <math|Q\<equiv\>0>.
  </proof>

  Let <math|R<rsup|<around|(|j|)>><rsub|n>\<in\><with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>><rsub|2*n+D-2>>
  be the unique polynomial such that

  <\equation*>
    \<alpha\><rsub|0><around|(|R<rsup|<around|(|j|)>><rsub|n>|)>=\<ldots\>=\<alpha\><rsub|2*n-1><around|(|R<rsup|<around|(|j|)>><rsub|n>|)>=0
  </equation*>

  and

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|\<beta\><rsub|k><around|(|R<rsup|<around|(|j|)>><rsub|n>|)>=\<delta\><rsub|k*j>>|<cell|>|<cell|\<forall\>k=1,\<ldots\>,D-1>>>>
  </align*>

  That such a polynomial exists and is unique follows from the linear
  independence of these functionals.

  <\theorem>
    The unique solution of the even Riemann-Hilbert problem
    (<reference|evenrhp>) is

    <\equation>
      <label|EvenSolution>

      <\eqsplit>
        <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|>|<cell|A<rsub|n>=>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<bbb-R\>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-2*V>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n>|)>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n>|)>>|<cell|\<ldots\>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|D-1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n>|)>>>|<row|<cell|-<frac|2*\<pi\>*i*\<gamma\>*D|h<rsub|n-1>>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n-2>>|<cell|-<frac|2*\<pi\>*i*\<gamma\>*D|h<rsub|n-1>>*C<rsub|\<bbb-R\>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-2*V>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n-2>|)>>|<cell|-<frac|2*\<pi\>*i*\<gamma\>*D|h<rsub|n-1>>*C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n-2>|)>>|<cell|\<ldots\>>|<cell|-<frac|2*\<pi\>*i*\<gamma\>*D|h<rsub|n-1>>*C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|D-1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n-2>|)>>>|<row|<cell|R<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<bbb-R\>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-2*V>*R<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>|)>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*R<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>|)>>|<cell|\<ldots\>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|D-1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*R<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>|)>>>|<row|<cell|\<vdots\>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|R<rsup|<around|(|D-1|)>><rsub|n>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<bbb-R\>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-2*V>*R<rsup|<around|(|D-1|)>><rsub|n>|)>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*R<rsup|<around|(|D-1|)>><rsub|n>|)>>|<cell|\<ldots\>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|D-1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*R<rsup|<around|(|D-1|)>><rsub|n>|)>>>>>>|)>>>>>
      </eqsplit>
    </equation>
  </theorem>

  <\lemma>
    [Symmetry for even case]<label|EvenSymmetry> Let
    <math|P\<in\>\<cal-M\><rsub|D-1><around|(|\<bbb-R\>|)>> be the
    permutation matrix on <math|\<bbb-R\><rsup|D-1>> for which
    <math|P*e<rsub|k>=e<rsub|D-k>> for <math|k=1,\<ldots\>,D-1>. Here
    <math|e<rsub|k>=<around|(|0,\<ldots\>,0,1,0,\<ldots\>,0|)><rsup|<math-ss|T>>>
    where the <math|1> lies in the <math|k>th entry. Let

    <\equation*>
      Q=<math-up|diag><around|(|-1,1|)>\<oplus\>P=<around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<cwith|2|2|1|-1|cell-bborder|1ln>|<table|<row|<cell|-1>|<cell|0>|<cell|<bord>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|0>|<cell|1>|<cell|<bord>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|<bord>>|<cell|P>>>>>|)>\<in\>\<cal-M\><rsub|D+1><around|(|\<bbb-R\>|)>
    </equation*>

    Note that <math|Q=Q<rsup|<math-ss|T>>=Q<rsup|-1>> is an orthogonal
    matrix. Then we have the relation

    <\equation*>
      A<rsub|n><around|(|z|)>=Q<wide|A<rsub|n><around|(|<wide|z|\<bar\>>|)>|\<bar\>>Q
    </equation*>
  </lemma>

  <\proof>
    Let <math|<wide|A|~><rsub|n><around|(|z|)>=Q<wide|A<rsub|n><around|(|<wide|z|\<bar\>>|)>|\<bar\>>Q>.
    We show that <math|<wide|A|~><rsub|n>> solves the even Riemann-Hilbert
    problem and thus by uniqueness (see Lemma <reference|uniqueness>)
    <math|<wide|A|~><rsub|n>=A<rsub|n>>. Clearly <math|<wide|A|~><rsub|n>> is
    analytic on <math|\<bbb-C\>\<setminus\>\<Gamma\>> and it is easy to see
    that

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<wide|A|~><rsub|n><around|(|z|)>=<around*|(|\<bbb-I\>+\<cal-O\><around|(|z<rsup|-1>|)>|)><around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|z<rsup|2*n+D-1>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|z<rsup|-2*n>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|z<rsup|-1>>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|\<ddots\>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|z<rsup|-1>>>>>>|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|<around|(|z\<to\>\<infty\>|)>>>>>
    </align*>

    Furthermore <math|<wide|A|~><rsub|n>> is clearly bounded at <math|0>
    since <math|A<rsub|n>> is.

    Because <math|V> is a polynomial with real coefficients,
    <math|<wide|V<around|(|<wide|x|\<bar\>>|)>|\<bar\>>=V<around|(|x|)>>.
    Furthermore, <math|\<chi\><rsub|\<bbb-R\>><around|(|<wide|x|\<bar\>>|)>=\<chi\><rsub|\<bbb-R\>><around|(|x|)>>
    and <math|\<chi\><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|k>><around|(|<wide|x|\<bar\>>|)>=\<chi\><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|D-k>><around|(|x|)>>.
    Now for <math|x\<in\>\<Gamma\>\<setminus\><around|{|0|}>> we have

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around*|(|<wide|A|~><rsub|n>|)><rsub|+><around|(|x|)>>|<cell|=Q<wide|<around*|(|A<rsub|n>|)><rsub|-><around|(|<wide|x|\<bar\>>|)>|\<bar\>>Q>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|=Q<wide|<around*|(|A<rsub|n>|)><rsub|+><around|(|<wide|x|\<bar\>>|)>|\<bar\>><around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-lborder|0ln>|<cwith|1|-1|2|2|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|3|3|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|4|4|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|5|5|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|6|6|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|7|7|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|8|8|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|9|9|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|10|10|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|11|11|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|12|12|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|13|13|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|14|14|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|15|15|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|16|16|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|17|17|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|18|18|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|19|19|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|19|19|cell-rborder|0ln>|<table|<row|<cell|1<space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>-e<rsup|-2*V>*\<chi\><rsub|\<bbb-R\>><space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>-e<rsup|-V>*\<chi\><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|D-1>><space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>\<ldots\><space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>-e<rsup|-V>*\<chi\><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|1>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|1>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|\<ddots\>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|1>>>>>|)>*Q>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|=<around*|(|<wide|A|~><rsub|n>|)><rsub|-><around|(|x|)><around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-lborder|0ln>|<cwith|1|-1|2|2|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|3|3|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|4|4|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|5|5|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|6|6|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|7|7|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|8|8|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|9|9|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|10|10|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|11|11|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|12|12|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|13|13|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|14|14|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|15|15|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|16|16|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|17|17|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|18|18|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|19|19|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|19|19|cell-rborder|0ln>|<table|<row|<cell|1<space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>e<rsup|-2*V>*\<chi\><rsub|\<bbb-R\>><space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>e<rsup|-V>*\<chi\><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>><space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>\<ldots\><space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>e<rsup|-V>*\<chi\><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|D-1>>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|1>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|1>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|\<ddots\>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|1>>>>>|)>>>>>
    </align*>

    Thus <math|<wide|A|~><rsub|n>=A<rsub|n>>.
  </proof>

  <\remark>
    Our method assumes <math|V> is a polynomial, however there are
    interesting cases, e.g. Jacobi weights, that do not fit into this class.
    How might our analysis be extended? The natural way would be to redefine
    <math|\<Psi\><rsub|n>> and <math|R<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>> so that
    these are no longer polynomials. For example if <math|V<rprime|'>> was
    rational with simple poles at <math|\<lambda\><rsub|1>,\<ldots\>,\<lambda\><rsub|k>>,
    then <math|\<Psi\><rsub|n>> would also be rational with simple poles,
    with the property that <math|<math-up|Res><rsub|z=\<lambda\><rsub|i>>\<Psi\><rsub|n><around|(|z|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|z|)>>=0>
    for all <math|i=1,\<ldots\>,k> and similarly for the auxiliary functions
    <math|R<rsup|<around|(|j|)>><rsub|n>>. Investigation of this is left as a
    topic for future research.
  </remark>

  We now move onto the <enquote|odd problem,> so called because it will later
  turn out that the <math|<around|(|1,1|)>> matrix element of the solution is
  <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n+1>>.

  <\rhp>
    [Odd problem]<label|oddrhp> Let <math|V> be a polynomial of even and
    positive degree and positive leading coefficient, and let

    <\equation*>
      \<Sigma\>=\<bbb-T\>\<cup\><big|cup><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<Gamma\><rsub|j>
    </equation*>

    where <math|\<Gamma\><rsub|j>> have the specified orientations and
    <math|\<bbb-T\>> is positively oriented. These contours are depicted in
    Figure <reference|morecontours>. Let <math|\<omega\>=e<rsup|<frac|2*\<pi\>*i|D>>>
    be a primitive root of unity and let

    <\equation*>
      S=<around|{|0,1,\<omega\>,\<omega\><rsup|2>,\<ldots\>,\<omega\><rsup|D-1>|}>
    </equation*>

    be the points of self-intersection of <math|\<Sigma\>>. We look for a
    <math|<around|(|D+2|)>\<times\><around|(|D+2|)>> matrix valued function

    <\equation*>
      B<rsub|n>:\<bbb-C\>\<setminus\>\<Sigma\>\<to\>\<cal-M\><rsub|D+2><around|(|\<bbb-C\>|)>
    </equation*>

    such that

    <\enumerate>
      <item><math|B<rsub|n>> is analytic on
      <math|\<bbb-C\>\<setminus\>\<Sigma\>> (that is, its matrix elements are
      analytic on <math|\<bbb-C\>\<setminus\>\<Sigma\>>).

      <item><math|B<rsub|n>> has continuous boundary values up to
      <math|\<Sigma\>\<setminus\>S>. That is, given
      <math|x\<in\>\<Sigma\>\<setminus\>S>, as
      <math|\<bbb-C\>\<setminus\>\<Sigma\>\<ni\>z\<to\>x> from either the
      <math|+> (left) side or <math|-> (right) side non-tangentially, the
      limit of <math|B<rsub|n><around|(|z|)>> exists. These limits are
      denoted

      <\align*>
        <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|B<rsub|n><rsup|+>:\<Sigma\>\<setminus\>S\<to\>\<cal-M\><rsub|D+2><around|(|\<bbb-C\>|)>>>|<row|<cell|B<rsub|n><rsup|->:\<Sigma\>\<setminus\>S\<to\>\<cal-M\><rsub|D+2><around|(|\<bbb-C\>|)>>>>>
      </align*>

      and are continuous functions. <enquote|Left> and <enquote|right> mean
      relative to the orientation of the contour.

      <item><math|B<rsub|n>> is bounded in a neighbourhood of <math|S>.

      <item>The boundary values are related by the <enquote|jump matrix>

      <\align*>
        <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|B<rsub|n><rsup|+><around|(|x|)>=B<rsub|n><rsup|-><around|(|x|)><around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-lborder|0ln>|<cwith|1|-1|2|2|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|3|3|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|4|4|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|5|5|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|6|6|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|7|7|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|8|8|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|9|9|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|10|10|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|11|11|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|12|12|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|13|13|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|14|14|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|15|15|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|16|16|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|17|17|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|18|18|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|19|19|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|19|19|cell-rborder|0ln>|<table|<row|<cell|1<space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>e<rsup|-2*V>*\<chi\><rsub|\<bbb-R\>><space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>e<rsup|-V>*\<chi\><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>><space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>\<ldots\><space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>e<rsup|-V>*\<chi\><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|D-1>><space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em><with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|-2*n-D>*\<chi\><rsub|\<bbb-T\>>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|1>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|1>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|\<ddots\>>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|1>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|1>>>>>|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|x\<in\>\<Sigma\>\<setminus\>S>>>>
      </align*>

      <item>We have the normalisation

      <\align>
        <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|B<rsub|n><around|(|z|)>=<around*|(|\<bbb-I\>+\<cal-O\><around|(|z<rsup|-1>|)>|)><around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|z<rsup|2*n+D>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|z<rsup|-2*n>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|z<rsup|-1>>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|\<ddots\>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|z<rsup|-1>>>>>>|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|<around|(|z\<to\>\<infty\>|)><eq-number>>>>>
      </align>
    </enumerate>
  </rhp>

  <\big-figure>
    <label|morecontours>

    <\padded-center>
      <\picture-mixed|<image|<tuple|<#>|eps>|194pt|194pt||>>
        \\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]

        \\draw[blue, thick,-\<gtr\>] (0,0) -- (1,0);

        \t\t\\draw[blue, thick,-\<gtr\>] (1,0) -- (3,0);

        \t\t\\draw[blue, thick] (3,0) -- node[below] {$C_0$}(4,0);

        \t\t\\draw[blue, thick] (0,0) -- (4,0);

        \t\t\\draw[blue,thick,-\<gtr\>] (0,4) -- node[right] {$C_2$}(0,3);

        \t\t\\draw[blue,thick,-\<gtr\>] (0,3) -- (0,1);

        \t\t\\draw[blue, thick] (0,0) -- (0,4);

