  </big-figure|The contours of the odd Riemann-Hilbert problem, here shown
  for the case <math|D=8>. Orientations of the contours are indicated by
  arrows.>

  The method of solution of this Riemann-Hilbert problem is very similar to
  the even case. The asymptotic condition implies that
  <math|<around|(|B<rsub|n>|)><rsub|11>=Q> is a monic polynomial of degree
  <math|2*n+D>. From the jump condition and the Plemelj formula we find that
  the first row is

  <\equation*>
    <around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-lborder|0ln>|<cwith|1|-1|2|2|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|3|3|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|4|4|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|5|5|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|6|6|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|7|7|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|8|8|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|9|9|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|10|10|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|11|11|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|12|12|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|13|13|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|13|13|cell-rborder|0ln>|<table|<row|<cell|Q>|<cell|,>|<cell|C<rsub|\<bbb-R\>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-2*V>*Q|)>>|<cell|,>|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*Q|)>>|<cell|,>|<cell|\<ldots\>>|<cell|,>|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|D-1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*Q|)>>|<cell|,>|<cell|C<rsub|\<bbb-T\>>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|-2*n-D>*Q|)>>>>>>|)>
  </equation*>

  From the normalisation <math|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|j>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*Q|)><around|(|z|)>=\<cal-O\><around|(|z<rsup|-2>|)>>
  for all <math|j=1,\<ldots\>,D-1> we find that there exists a polynomial
  <math|P> of degree <math|2*n+1> such that
  <math|Q=e<rsup|V>*<frac|d|d*x>*<around|(|P*e<rsup|-V>|)>>.

  <\remark>
    The normalisation <math|C<rsub|\<bbb-T\>>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|-2*n-D>*Q|)><around|(|z|)>=\<cal-O\><around|(|z<rsup|-2>|)>>
    implies that

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|Q<around|(|x|)>=x<rsup|2*n+D>+\<cal-O\><around|(|x<rsup|2*n+D-2>|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|<around|(|z\<to\>\<infty\>|)>>>>>
    </align*>

    This fixes the next-to-leading coefficient of <math|P> (where
    <math|Q=e<rsup|V>*<frac|d|d*x>*<around*|(|P*e<rsup|-V>|)>>) though not
    necessarily to <math|0>. This explains the remark made in the
    introduction that fixing the next-to-leading coefficient of <math|P> to
    <math|0> is not always the most convenient choice. The addition of the
    contour <math|\<bbb-T\>> could also be done for the Riemann-Hilbert
    problem of Pierce <cite|PIERCE2008230> in order to guarantee a unique
    solution.
  </remark>

  Finally, the scaling <math|C<rsub|\<bbb-R\>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-2*V>*Q|)><around|(|z|)>=\<cal-O\><around|(|z<rsup|-2*n-1>|)>>
  implies that <math|<around|\<langle\>|<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|0>,P|\<rangle\>><rsub|4>=\<ldots\>=<around|\<langle\>|<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|2*n-1>,P|\<rangle\>><rsub|4>=0>,
  so <math|P> is indeed skew-orthogonal. Thus <math|Q=\<Psi\><rsub|2*n+1>>.

  In the same manner as for the even case we find that the second row is

  <\equation*>
    <around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-lborder|0ln>|<cwith|1|-1|2|2|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|3|3|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|4|4|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|5|5|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|6|6|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|7|7|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|8|8|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|9|9|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|10|10|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|11|11|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|12|12|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|13|13|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|13|13|cell-rborder|0ln>|<table|<row|<cell|<wide|Q|~>>|<cell|,>|<cell|C<rsub|\<bbb-R\>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-2*V>*<wide|Q|~>|)>>|<cell|,>|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*<wide|Q|~>|)>>|<cell|,>|<cell|\<ldots\>>|<cell|,>|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|D-1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*<wide|Q|~>|)>>|<cell|,>|<cell|C<rsub|\<bbb-T\>>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|-2*n-D>*<wide|Q|~>|)>>>>>>|)>
  </equation*>

  where <math|<wide|Q|~>=-<frac|2*\<pi\>*i*\<gamma\>*D|h<rsub|n-1>>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n-2>>.
  Indeed the remaining rows except the final one are the same as in the even
  case. To show a unique solution in all remaining rows let us introduce the
  linear functional <math|\<beta\><rsub|D>:<with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>><rsub|2*n+D-2>\<to\>\<bbb-C\>>
  defined by

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|\<beta\><rsub|D><around|(|P|)>=-<frac|1|2*\<pi\>*i>*<big|oint><rsub|\<bbb-T\>>P<around|(|z|)>*z<rsup|-2*n-D>*<space|0.17em>d*z<eq-number>>>>>
  </align>

  Now let <math|\<alpha\><rsub|0>,\<ldots\>,\<alpha\><rsub|2*n-1>> and
  <math|\<beta\><rsub|1>,\<ldots\>,\<beta\><rsub|D-1>> act on
  <math|<with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>><rsub|2*n+D-1>> according to
  the formulas given in (<reference|alpha>) and (<reference|beta>). That the
  2nd to <math|<around|(|D+2|)>>th rows have a unique solution follows from
  the lemma below.

  <\lemma>
    Consider the linear functionals <math|\<alpha\><rsub|0>,\<ldots\>,\<alpha\><rsub|2*n-1>>
    and <math|\<beta\><rsub|1>,\<ldots\>,\<beta\><rsub|D>> viewed as acting
    on <math|<with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>><rsub|2*n+D-1>> according
    to (<reference|alpha>) and (<reference|beta>). Then

    <\equation*>
      <big|cap><rsub|j=0><rsup|2*n-1>ker \<alpha\><rsub|j>\<cap\><big|cap><rsub|k=1><rsup|D>ker
      \<beta\><rsub|k>=0
    </equation*>
  </lemma>

  <\proof>
    If <math|\<beta\><rsub|D><around|(|Q|)>=0> then
    <math|Q\<in\><with|math-font|cal*|P><rsup|\<bbb-C\>><rsub|2*n+D-2>>. The
    proof then reduces to that of Lemma <reference|linindep>.
  </proof>

  <with|font-base-size|6|<\theorem>
    The unique solution of the odd Riemann-Hilbert problem
    (<reference|oddrhp>) is then

    <\equation>
      <\eqsplit>
        <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|>|<cell|B<rsub|n>=>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n+1>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<bbb-R\>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-2*V>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n+1>|)>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n+1>|)>>|<cell|\<ldots\>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<bbb-T\>>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|-2*n-D>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n+1>|)>>>|<row|<cell|-<frac|2*\<pi\>*i*\<gamma\>*D|h<rsub|n-1>>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n-2>>|<cell|-<frac|2*\<pi\>*i*\<gamma\>*D|h<rsub|n-1>>*C<rsub|\<bbb-R\>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-2*V>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n-2>|)>>|<cell|-<frac|2*\<pi\>*i*\<gamma\>*D|h<rsub|n-1>>*C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n-2>|)>>|<cell|\<ldots\>>|<cell|-<frac|2*\<pi\>*i*\<gamma\>*D|h<rsub|n-1>>*C<rsub|\<bbb-T\>>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|-2*n-D>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n-2>|)>>>|<row|<cell|R<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<bbb-R\>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-2*V>*R<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>|)>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*R<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>|)>>|<cell|\<ldots\>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<bbb-T\>>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|-2*n-D>*R<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>|)>>>|<row|<cell|\<vdots\>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|R<rsup|<around|(|D-1|)>><rsub|n>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<bbb-R\>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-2*V>*R<rsup|<around|(|D-1|)>><rsub|n>|)>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*R<rsup|<around|(|D-1|)>><rsub|n>|)>>|<cell|\<ldots\>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<bbb-T\>>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|-2*n-D>*R<rsup|<around|(|D-1|)>><rsub|n>|)>>>|<row|<cell|R<rsup|<around|(|D|)>><rsub|n>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<bbb-R\>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-2*V>*R<rsup|<around|(|D|)>><rsub|n>|)>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>>*<around|(|e<rsup|-V>*R<rsup|<around|(|D|)>><rsub|n>|)>>|<cell|\<ldots\>>|<cell|C<rsub|\<bbb-T\>>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|-2*n-D>*R<rsup|<around|(|D|)>><rsub|n>|)>>>>>>|)>>>>>
      </eqsplit>
    </equation>
  </theorem>>

  Note that these polynomials <math|R<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>,\<ldots\>,R<rsup|<around|(|D-1|)>><rsub|n>>
  are the same polynomials that appear in the even problem, so we have not
  made a confusion of notation. Note also that the integrals in the final
  column can be computed explicitly.

  <\proposition>
    <math|R<rsup|<around|(|D|)>><rsub|n>=-\<Psi\><rsub|2*n>>.
  </proposition>

  <\proof>
    From the normalisation we see that <math|R<rsup|<around|(|D|)>><rsub|n>>
    is a polynomial of degree at most <math|2*n+D-1> and from
    <math|C<rsub|\<bbb-T\>>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|-2*n-D>*R<rsup|<around|(|D|)>><rsub|n>|)><around|(|z|)>=z<rsup|-1>+\<cal-O\><around|(|z<rsup|-2>|)>>
    we find that that <math|R<rsup|<around|(|D|)>><rsub|n><around|(|x|)>=-Q<around|(|x|)>>
    where <math|Q> is a monic polynomial of degree <math|2*n+D-1>. From the
    fact that <math|\<beta\><rsub|1><around|(|R<rsup|<around|(|D|)>><rsub|n>|)>=\<ldots\>=\<beta\><rsub|D-1><around|(|R<rsup|<around|(|D|)>><rsub|n>|)>=0>
    we find that <math|Q=e<rsup|V>*<frac|d|d*x>*<around|(|P*e<rsup|-V>|)>>
    for some polynomial <math|P> of degree exactly <math|2*n>. Finally, the
    requirement that <math|\<alpha\><rsub|0><around|(|R<rsup|<around|(|D|)>><rsub|n>|)>=\<ldots\>=\<alpha\><rsub|2*n-1><around|(|R<rsup|<around|(|D|)>><rsub|n>|)>=0>
    implies that <math|P> is skew-orthogonal to all of
    <math|<with|math-font|cal*|P><rsub|2*n-1><rsup|\<bbb-C\>>>.
  </proof>

  From this one might think the <math|B<rsub|n>> problem is strictly superior
  to the <math|A<rsub|n>> problem, since the former encodes both
  <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n+1>> and <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n>>, however our
  Christoffel-Darboux formula (<reference|CD>) implies that from the point of
  view of random matrix theory it is completely sufficient to study
  <math|A<rsub|n>>.

  <\lemma>
    <math|2*n\<leq\>deg R<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>\<leq\>2*n+D-2> for
    <math|j=1,\<ldots\>,D-1>.
  </lemma>

  <\proof>
    Suppose by way of contradiction that <math|deg
    R<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>\<leq\>2*n-1>. Then by the conditions
    <math|\<alpha\><rsub|0><around|(|R<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>|)>=\<ldots\>=\<alpha\><rsub|2*n-1><around|(|R<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>|)>=0>
    we find that <math|R<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>\<equiv\>0>. But this
    contradicts <math|\<beta\><rsub|j><around|(|R<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>|)>=1>.
  </proof>

  <\remark>
    <label|zero>For the case <math|n=0>, the polynomials
    <math|R<rsub|0><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>,\<ldots\>,R<rsub|0><rsup|<around|(|D-1|)>>>
    can be constructed as follows. Let <math|M> be the matrix

    <\equation*>
      M=<around|(|M<rsub|i*j>|)><rsub|i,j=1><rsup|D-1>=<around*|(|<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|i>>x<rsup|j-1>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x|)><rsub|i,j=1><rsup|D-1>,
    </equation*>

    then we have

    <\equation*>
      R<rsup|<around|(|j|)>><rsub|0><around|(|x|)>=-2*\<pi\>*i*<big|sum><rsub|k=1><rsup|D-1><around|(|M<rsup|-1>|)><rsub|k*j>*x<rsup|k-1>.
    </equation*>
  </remark>

  <\lemma>
    [Symmetry for odd problem]<label|OddSymmetry> Let
    <math|P\<in\>\<cal-M\><rsub|D-1><around|(|\<bbb-R\>|)>> be defined as in
    Lemma <reference|EvenSymmetry> and let

    <\equation*>
      Q=<math-up|diag><around|(|-1,1|)>\<oplus\>P\<oplus\><around|(|-1|)>=<around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-lborder|0ln>|<cwith|1|-1|2|2|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|3|3|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|4|4|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|5|5|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|6|6|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|7|7|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|7|7|cell-rborder|0ln>|<cwith|2|2|1|5|cell-bborder|1ln>|<cwith|3|3|4|6|cell-bborder|1ln>|<table|<row|<cell|-1>|<cell|0>|<cell|<bord>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|0>|<cell|1>|<cell|<bord>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|<bord>>|<cell|<space|0.17em><space|0.17em><space|0.17em>P>|<cell|<bord>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|<bord>>|<cell|-1>>>>>|)>\<in\>\<cal-M\><rsub|D+2><around|(|\<bbb-R\>|)>
    </equation*>

    Note that <math|Q=Q<rsup|<math-ss|T>>=Q<rsup|-1>> is an orthogonal
    matrix. Then we have the relation

    <\equation*>
      B<rsub|n><around|(|z|)>=Q<wide|B<rsub|n><around|(|<wide|z|\<bar\>>|)>|\<bar\>>Q
    </equation*>
  </lemma>

  <\proof>
    Morally the same as for the even case.
  </proof>

  Finally, our results allow us to characterise the <enquote|dual>
  skew-orthogonal polynomials <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n>> and auxiliary
  polynomials <math|R<rsup|<around|(|j|)>><rsub|n>> in terms of the
  corresponding sequence of <with|font-shape|italic|orthogonal> polynomials.
  This is morally the same construction as in Remark <reference|zero>.

  <\corollary>
    [Skew-orthogonal polynomials in terms of orthogonal
    polynomials]<label|orthog> Let <math|<around|{|H<rsub|n>|}><rsub|n\<in\>\<bbb-N\>>>
    be the sequence of monic orthogonal polynomials corresponding to the
    weight <math|e<rsup|-2*V>> where <math|V<around|(|x|)>=\<gamma\>*x<rsup|D>+\<cal-O\><around|(|x<rsup|D-1>|)>>
    is a real polynomial of even degree <math|D\<geq\>2> and
    <math|\<gamma\>\<gtr\>0>. That is,

    <\equation*>
      H<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>=x<rsup|n>+\<cal-O\><around|(|x<rsup|n-1>|)>
    </equation*>

    and

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>H<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>*H<rsub|m><around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-2*V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x=0>|<cell|>|<cell|\<forall\>n,m\<in\>\<bbb-N\>,<space|0.17em>n\<neq\>m>>>>
    </align*>

    Let <math|M> be the matrix

    <\equation*>
      M=<around*|(|M<rsub|j*k>|)><rsub|j,k=1><rsup|D-1>=<around*|(|<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|j>>H<rsub|2*n+k-1><around|(|z|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|z|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*z|)><rsub|j,k=1><rsup|D-1>
    </equation*>

    and let <math|\<lambda\><rsub|n>> be the next-to-leading coefficient of
    <math|H<rsub|n+D>>, i.e.

    <\equation*>
      H<rsub|n+D><around|(|x|)>=x<rsup|n+D>+\<lambda\><rsub|n>*x<rsup|n+D-1>+\<cal-O\><around|(|x<rsup|n+D-2>|)>
    </equation*>

    Then the corresponding <enquote|dual> skew-orthogonal polynomials and
    auxiliary polynomials may be expressed

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n>>|<cell|=H<rsub|2*n+D-1>-<big|sum><rsub|k,j=1><rsup|D-1><around*|[|<around|(|M<rsup|-1>|)><rsub|k*j>*<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|j>>H<rsub|2*n+D-1><around|(|z|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|z|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*z|]>*H<rsub|2*n+k-1>>>|<row|<cell|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n+1>>|<cell|=H<rsub|2*n+D>-\<lambda\><rsub|n>*H<rsub|2*n+D-1>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>-<big|sum><rsub|k,j=1><rsup|D-1><around*|[|<around|(|M<rsup|-1>|)><rsub|k*j>*<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|j>><around|(|H<rsub|2*n+D><around|(|z|)>-\<lambda\><rsub|n>*H<rsub|2*n+D-1><around|(|z|)>|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|z|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*z|]>*H<rsub|2*n+k-1>>>|<row|<cell|R<rsup|<around|(|j|)>><rsub|n>>|<cell|=-2*\<pi\>*i*<big|sum><rsub|k=1><rsup|D-1><around|(|M<rsup|-1>|)><rsub|k*j>*H<rsub|2*n+k-1>>>>>
    </align*>
  </corollary>

  Indeed, these <math|<around|{|H<rsub|k>|}><rsub|k\<in\>\<bbb-N\>>> are
  exactly the <enquote|natural basis> identified by Adler and van Moerbeke
  <cite|adler1999pfaff>.

  <\exmp>
    In the case <math|D=2>, for the potential
    <math|V<around|(|z|)>=<frac|1|2>*z<rsup|2>> we can write the
    corresponding orthogonal polynomials explicitly as

    <\equation>
      <label|Hermite>H<rsub|n><around|(|z|)>=<frac|<around|(|-1|)><rsup|n>|2<rsup|n>>*e<rsup|z<rsup|2>>*<frac|d<rsup|n>|d*z<rsup|n>>*e<rsup|-z<rsup|2>>
    </equation>

    Then using <math|<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>H<rsub|2*n><around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-<frac|1|2>*x<rsup|2>>*<space|0.17em>d*x=<sqrt|2>*<around*|(|n-<frac|1|2>|)>>!
    one finds that

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n>>|<cell|=H<rsub|2*n+1>>>|<row|<cell|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n+1>>|<cell|=H<rsub|2*n+2>-<around*|(|n+<frac|1|2>|)>*H<rsub|2*n>>>|<row|<cell|R<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>>|<cell|=-<frac|2*\<pi\>*i|<sqrt|2>*<around*|(|n-<frac|1|2>|)>!>*H<rsub|2*n>>>|<row|<cell|P<rsub|2*n>>|<cell|=n!<big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n><frac|1|k!>*H<rsub|2*k>>>|<row|<cell|P<rsub|2*n+1>>|<cell|=H<rsub|2*n+1>>>>>
    </align*>
  </exmp>

  What we have done in the preceding discussion amounts to representing
  <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n>> and <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*n+1>> as
  <enquote|multiple-orthogonal polynomials of Type II> (see e.g.
  <cite|Martinez_Finkelshtein_2016> for a definition of this term). Let us
  summarise this with the following corollary.

  <\corollary>
    [Dual skew-orthogonal polynomials as Type II multiple-orthogonal
    polynomials]<label|typeII> Consider the following problem. Find a monic
    polynomial <math|Q> of degree exactly <math|2*n+D-1> such that

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>x<rsup|k>*Q<around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-2*V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x>|<cell|=0>|<cell|>|<cell|\<forall\>k=0,\<ldots\>,2*n-1>>|<row|<cell|<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|j>>Q<around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-2*V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x>|<cell|=0>|<cell|>|<cell|\<forall\>j=1,\<ldots\>,D-1>>>>
    </align*>

    Then this problem is uniquely solved by <math|Q=\<Psi\><rsub|2*n>>.
    Similarly if we are asked to find a monic polynomial <math|Q> of degree
    exactly <math|2*n+D> such that

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>x<rsup|k>*Q<around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-2*V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x>|<cell|=0>|<cell|>|<cell|\<forall\>k=0,\<ldots\>,2*n-1>>|<row|<cell|<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|j>>Q<around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-2*V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x>|<cell|=0>|<cell|>|<cell|\<forall\>j=1,\<ldots\>,D-1>>|<row|<cell|<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-T\>>Q<around|(|x|)>*x<rsup|-2*n-D>*<space|0.17em>d*x>|<cell|=0>|<cell|>|<cell|>>>>
    </align*>

    then this problem is uniquely solved by <math|Q=\<Psi\><rsub|2*n+1>>. We
    should note that our case differs from usual multiple-orthogonality
    because our <enquote|measures> are not all supported on <math|\<bbb-R\>>.
  </corollary>

  Following the standard theory of multiple-orthogonal polynomials
  <cite|VanAssche2001> it is natural to consider the Riemann-Hilbert problems
  satisfied by <math|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>=A<rsub|n><rsup|-<math-ss|T>>> and
  <math|<wide|B<rsub|n>|^>=B<rsub|n><rsup|-<math-ss|T>>> (inverse transpose).

  <\rhp>
    [Dual even problem] By virtue of the fact that <math|det
    A<rsub|n>\<equiv\>1>, <math|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>\<assign\>A<rsub|n><rsup|-<math-ss|T>>>
    satisfies the following Riemann-Hilbert problem.

    <\enumerate>
      <item><math|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>> is analytic on
      <math|\<bbb-C\>\<setminus\>\<Gamma\>> (that is, its matrix elements are
      analytic on <math|\<bbb-C\>\<setminus\>\<Gamma\>>).

      <item><math|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>> has continuous boundary values up to
      <math|\<Gamma\>\<setminus\><around|{|0|}>>. That is, given
      <math|x\<in\>\<Gamma\>\<setminus\><around|{|0|}>>, as
      <math|\<bbb-C\>\<setminus\>\<Gamma\>\<ni\>z\<to\>x> from either the
      <math|+> (left) side or <math|-> (right) side non-tangentially, the
      limit of <math|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^><around|(|z|)>> exists. These limits
      are denoted

      <\align*>
        <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^><rsup|+>:\<Gamma\>\<setminus\><around|{|0|}>\<to\>\<cal-M\><rsub|D+1><around|(|\<bbb-C\>|)>>>|<row|<cell|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^><rsup|->:\<Gamma\>\<setminus\><around|{|0|}>\<to\>\<cal-M\><rsub|D+1><around|(|\<bbb-C\>|)>>>>>
      </align*>

      and are continuous functions. <enquote|Left> and <enquote|right> mean
      relative to the orientation of the contour.

      <item><math|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>> is bounded in a neighbourhood of
      <math|0>.

      <item>The boundary values are related by the <enquote|jump matrix>

      <\align*>
        <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^><rsup|+><around|(|x|)>=<wide|A<rsub|n>|^><rsup|-><around|(|x|)><around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-lborder|0ln>|<cwith|1|-1|2|2|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|3|3|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|4|4|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|5|5|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|6|6|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|7|7|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|8|8|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|9|9|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|10|10|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|11|11|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|12|12|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|13|13|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|14|14|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|15|15|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|16|16|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|17|17|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|18|18|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|19|19|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|19|19|cell-rborder|0ln>|<table|<row|<cell|1<space|0.17em>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|-e<rsup|-2*V>*\<chi\><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>>|<cell|1>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|-e<rsup|-V>*\<chi\><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|1>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|\<vdots\>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|\<ddots\>>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|-e<rsup|-V>*\<chi\><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|D-1>><space|0.17em>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|1>>>>>|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|x\<in\>\<Gamma\>\<setminus\><around|{|0|}>>>>>
      </align*>

      <item>We have the scaling as <math|z\<to\>\<infty\>>

      <\equation*>
        <wide|A<rsub|n>|^><around|(|z|)>=<around*|(|\<bbb-I\>+\<cal-O\><around|(|z<rsup|-1>|)>|)><around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|z<rsup|-2*n-D+1>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|z<rsup|2*n>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|z>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|\<ddots\>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|z>>>>>|)>
      </equation*>
    </enumerate>
  </rhp>

  In what follows we shall only be interested in computing the second column
  of <math|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>> (the motivation for this is that this column
  will appear in the upcoming Christoffel-Darboux formula), though it is an
  easy exercise for the reader to compute the remaining columns. By virtue of
  the jump condition, the 2nd to <math|<around|(|D+1|)>>th columns all have
  no jump across <math|\<Gamma\>\<setminus\><around|{|0|}>> and by
  boundedness around <math|0> we see that the singularity at <math|0> is
  removable. Hence the 2nd to <math|<around|(|D+1|)>>th columns are entire
  functions, indeed polynomials by the asymptotic condition.

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around*|(|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>|)><rsub|i*2><around|(|z|)>>|<cell|=z<rsup|2*n>*<space|0.17em>\<delta\><rsub|i,2>+\<cal-O\><around|(|z<rsup|2*n-1>|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|i=1,\<ldots\>,D+1>>|<row|<cell|<around*|(|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>|)><rsub|i*j><around|(|z|)>>|<cell|=z*<space|0.17em>\<delta\><rsub|i*j>+c<rsub|i*j>>|<cell|>|<cell|i=1,\<ldots\>,D+1*<text|and
    >j=3,\<ldots\>,D+1>>>>
  </align*>

  where the <math|c<rsub|i*j>> are constants. The jump condition on the first
  column may be solved by Plemelj's formula.

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around*|(|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>|)><rsub|i*1>=-C<rsub|\<bbb-R\>>*<around*|(|<around*|(|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>|)><rsub|i*2>*e<rsup|-2*V>|)>-<big|sum><rsub|j=3><rsup|D+1>c<rsub|i*j>*<space|0.17em>C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|j-2>><around*|(|e<rsup|-V>|)>-\<chi\><rsub|i\<geq\>3>*C<rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|i-2>>*<around*|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*e<rsup|-V>|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|i=1,\<ldots\>,D+1>>>>
  </align*>

  The asymptotic condition <math|<around*|(|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>|)><rsub|11><around|(|z|)>=z<rsup|-2*n-D+1>*<around|(|1+\<cal-O\><around|(|z<rsup|-1>|)>|)>>
  yields the conditions

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>><around*|(|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>|)><rsub|12><around|(|x|)>*x<rsup|k>*e<rsup|-2*V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x+<big|sum><rsub|j=3><rsup|D+1>c<rsub|1*j>*<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|j-2>>x<rsup|k>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x=0>|<cell|>|<cell|\<forall\>k=0,\<ldots\>,2*n+D-3>>>>
  </align*>

  By taking linear combinations of these equations we can replace
  <math|x<rsup|k>> with any polynomial of degree <math|\<leq\>2*n+D-3>, in
  particular we can replace it with <math|\<Psi\><rsub|0>,\<ldots\>,\<Psi\><rsub|2*n-2>>.
  This implies that <math|<around*|(|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>|)><rsub|12>> is a
  scalar multiple of <math|P<rsub|2*n-2>>. This multiple is fixed by

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>><around*|(|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>|)><rsub|12><around|(|x|)>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n-1><around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-2*V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x=2*\<pi\>*i>>>>
  </align*>

  and so

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around*|(|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>|)><rsub|12>=-<frac|2*\<pi\>*i*\<gamma\>*D|h<rsub|n-1>>*P<rsub|2*n-2><eq-number><label|12Ahat>>>>>
  </align>

  By a similar argument we see that

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around*|(|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>|)><rsub|22>=P<rsub|2*n><eq-number><label|22Ahat>>>>>
  </align>

  The remaining entries in the second column are polynomials of degree at
  most <math|2*n-1>. These satisfy the conditions

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>><around*|(|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>|)><rsub|i*2><around|(|x|)>*\<Psi\><rsub|k><around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-2*V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x+<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|i-2>>x*\<Psi\><rsub|k><around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x=0>|<cell|>|<cell|\<forall\>k=0,\<ldots\>,2*n-1*<text|and
    >i\<geq\>3>>>>
  </align*>

  Expanding this in the basis <math|P<rsub|0>,\<ldots\>,P<rsub|2*n-1>> we
  find

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around*|(|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>|)><rsub|i*2>=\<gamma\>*D*<big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n-1>h<rsub|k><rsup|-1>*<around*|(|P<rsub|2*k>*<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|i-2>>x*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1><around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x-P<rsub|2*k+1>*<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|i-2>>x*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k><around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|i\<geq\>3<eq-number><label|i2Ahat>>>>>
  </align>

  What the above calculation demonstrates is that <math|P<rsub|2*n>> may be
  thought of as a Type I multiple-orthogonal polynomial (again see
  <cite|Martinez_Finkelshtein_2016> for a definition of this term). Let us
  formalise this with the following corollary.

  <\corollary>
    [Even skew-orthogonal polynomials as Type I multiple-orthogonal
    polynomials]<label|typeI> Consider the following problem. Find a monic
    polynomial <math|P> of degree exactly <math|2*n> and a collection of
    constants <math|c<rsub|1>,\<ldots\>,c<rsub|D-1>> such that

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>x<rsup|k>*P<around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-2*V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x+<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>c<rsub|j>*<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|j>>x<rsup|k>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x=0>|<cell|>|<cell|\<forall\>k=0,\<ldots\>,2*n+D-2>>>>
    </align*>

    Then this problem has a unique solution
    <math|<around|(|P,c<rsub|1>,\<ldots\>,c<rsub|D-1>|)>>, where
    <math|P=P<rsub|2*n>>.
  </corollary>

  On the other hand, it is not clear if it is possible to think of
  <math|P<rsub|2*n+1>> as a Type I multiple-orthogonal polynomial and, as we
  shall soon see, <math|P<rsub|2*n+1>> (or any multiple of it) doesn't appear
  as a matrix element of <math|B<rsub|n><rsup|-1>>. It is possible to
  characterise <math|P<rsub|2*n+1>> by a <with|font-shape|italic|combination>
  of both Type I and Type II orthogonality conditions, as follows. We look
  for a monic polynomial <math|P> of degree <math|2*n+1> and a collection of
  constants <math|c<rsub|1>,\<ldots\>,c<rsub|D-1>> such that

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>P<around|(|x|)>*x<rsup|k>*e<rsup|-2*V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x+<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>c<rsub|j>*<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|j>>x<rsup|k>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x=0>|<cell|>|<cell|\<forall\>k=0,\<ldots\>,2*n+D-2>>>>
  </align*>

  and

  <\equation*>
    <big|int><rsub|\<bbb-T\>>P<around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>>*<frac|d|d*x>*<around*|(|x<rsup|-2*n-D>*e<rsup|V<around|(|x|)>>|)>*<space|0.17em>d*x=0
  </equation*>

  <math|<around|(|P,c<rsub|1>,\<ldots\>,c<rsub|D-1>|)>=<around|(|P<rsub|2*n+1>,\<ast\>,\<ldots\>,\<ast\>|)>>
  is the unique solution of this problem. However this construction seems
  somewhat ugly and we shall not investigate the implications of this here.

  <\rhp>
    [Dual odd problem] By virtue of the fact that <math|det
    B<rsub|n>\<equiv\>1>, <math|<wide|B<rsub|n>|^>\<assign\>B<rsub|n><rsup|-<math-ss|T>>>
    satisfies the following Riemann-Hilbert problem.

    <\enumerate>
      <item><math|<wide|B<rsub|n>|^>> is analytic on
      <math|\<bbb-C\>\<setminus\>\<Sigma\>> (that is, its matrix elements are
      analytic on <math|\<bbb-C\>\<setminus\>\<Sigma\>>).

      <item><math|<wide|B<rsub|n>|^>> has continuous boundary values up to
      <math|\<Sigma\>\<setminus\>S>. That is, given
      <math|x\<in\>\<Sigma\>\<setminus\>S>, as
      <math|\<bbb-C\>\<setminus\>\<Sigma\>\<ni\>z\<to\>x> from either the
      <math|+> (left) side or <math|-> (right) side non-tangentially, the
      limit of <math|<wide|B<rsub|n>|^><around|(|z|)>> exists. These limits
      are denoted

      <\align*>
        <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<wide|B<rsub|n>|^><rsup|+>:\<Sigma\>\<setminus\>S\<to\>\<cal-M\><rsub|D+2><around|(|\<bbb-C\>|)>>>|<row|<cell|<wide|B<rsub|n>|^><rsup|->:\<Sigma\>\<setminus\>S\<to\>\<cal-M\><rsub|D+2><around|(|\<bbb-C\>|)>>>>>
      </align*>

      and are continuous functions. <enquote|Left> and <enquote|right> mean
      relative to the orientation of the contour.

      <item><math|<wide|B<rsub|n>|^>> is bounded in a neighbourhood of
      <math|S>.

      <item>The boundary values are related by the <enquote|jump matrix>

      <\align*>
        <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<wide|B<rsub|n>|^><rsup|+><around|(|x|)>=<wide|B<rsub|n>|^><rsup|-><around|(|x|)><around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-lborder|0ln>|<cwith|1|-1|2|2|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|3|3|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|4|4|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|5|5|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|6|6|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|7|7|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|8|8|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|9|9|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|10|10|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|11|11|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|12|12|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|13|13|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|14|14|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|15|15|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|16|16|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|17|17|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|18|18|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|19|19|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|19|19|cell-rborder|0ln>|<table|<row|<cell|1<space|0.17em>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|-e<rsup|-2*V>*\<chi\><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>>|<cell|1>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|-e<rsup|-V>*\<chi\><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|1>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|\<vdots\>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|\<ddots\>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|-e<rsup|-V>*\<chi\><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|D-1>><space|0.17em>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|1>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|-<with|math-font|cal*|X><rsup|-2*n-D>*\<chi\><rsub|\<bbb-T\>><space|0.17em>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|1>>>>>|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|x\<in\>\<Sigma\>\<setminus\>S>>>>
      </align*>

      <item>We have the normalisation

      <\align*>
        <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<wide|B<rsub|n>|^><around|(|z|)>=<around*|(|\<bbb-I\>+\<cal-O\><around|(|z<rsup|-1>|)>|)><around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|z<rsup|-2*n-D>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|z<rsup|2*n>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|z>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|\<ddots\>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|z>>>>>|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|<around|(|z\<to\>\<infty\>|)>>>>>
      </align*>
    </enumerate>
  </rhp>

  Here again we restrict ourselves to computing the second column. We shall
  simply state the result since the calculation is practically the same as in
  the case of <math|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>>.

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around*|(|<wide|B<rsub|n>|^>|)><rsub|12>>|<cell|=0>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|<around*|(|<wide|B<rsub|n>|^>|)><rsub|22>>|<cell|=P<rsub|2*n>>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|<around*|(|<wide|B<rsub|n>|^>|)><rsub|i*2>>|<cell|=<around*|(|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>|)><rsub|i*2>>|<cell|>|<cell|i=3,\<ldots\>,D+1>>|<row|<cell|<around*|(|<wide|B<rsub|n>|^>|)><rsub|D+2,2>>|<cell|=<frac|2*\<pi\>*i*\<gamma\>*D|h<rsub|n-1>>*P<rsub|2*n-2>>|<cell|>|<cell|>>>>
  </align*>

  <section|Christoffel-Darboux formula><label|christoffelsection>

  In this section we prove the following theorem.

  <\theorem>
    [Christoffel-Darboux] Let the pre-kernel <math|S<rsub|n>> be defined by
    (<reference|prekernel>). Then

    <\equation>
      <label|CD><boxed|S<rsub|n><around|(|x,y|)>=-<frac|1|4*\<pi\>*i>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>-V<around|(|y|)>>*<frac|<around*|(|A<rsub|n><rsup|-1><around|(|x|)>*A<rsub|n><around|(|y|)>|)><rsub|21>|x-y>>
    </equation>

    where <math|A<rsub|n>> is the unique solution of Riemann-Hilbert problem
    <reference|evenrhp>.
  </theorem>

  <\remark>
    We call this a <enquote|Christoffel-Darboux> formula because an analogous
    formula appears in the theory of orthogonal polynomials
    (<math|\<beta\>=2>), i.e. if one takes <math|A<rsub|n>> to be the
    <math|2\<times\>2> Fokas-Its-Kitaev <cite|fokas> RHP, then
    (<reference|CD>) yields the classical Christoffel-Darboux formula, up to
    a factor of <math|<frac|1|2>>.
  </remark>

  <\remark>
    We could, if we like, have expressed the Christoffel-Darboux formula
    (<reference|CD>) in terms of the solution of the odd problem
    (<reference|oddrhp>), since we see from our solution to <math|B<rsub|n>>
    and <math|<wide|B<rsub|n>|^>> that <math|<around|(|A<rsub|n><rsup|-1><around|(|x|)>*A<rsub|n><around|(|y|)>|)><rsub|21>=<around|(|B<rsub|n><rsup|-1><around|(|x|)>*B<rsub|n><around|(|y|)>|)><rsub|21>>.
  </remark>

  To prove this result we need to derive a variety of relations. First note
  that the polynomial <math|R<rsub|k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>-R<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>>
  for <math|k=0,\<ldots\>,n-1> is in the kernel of <math|\<beta\><rsub|j>>
  for all <math|j> and has degree at most <math|2*n+D-2>. It is therefore in
  the span of <math|\<Psi\><rsub|0>,\<ldots\>,\<Psi\><rsub|2*n-1>>. Thus
  write <math|R<rsub|k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>-R<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>=<big|sum><rsub|i=0><rsup|n-1>\<eta\><rsub|i*k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*i>+<big|sum><rsub|i=0><rsup|n-1>\<xi\><rsub|i*k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*i+1>>.
  We then have

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|\<eta\><rsub|i*k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>=<frac|\<gamma\>*D|h<rsub|i>>*<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>R<rsub|k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>*P<rsub|2*i+1>*e<rsup|-2*V>*<space|0.17em>d*x>>|<row|<cell|\<xi\><rsub|i*k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>=-<frac|\<gamma\>*D|h<rsub|i>>*<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>R<rsub|k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>*P<rsub|2*i>*e<rsup|-2*V>*<space|0.17em>d*x>>>>
  </align*>

  Note that for <math|i\<leq\>k-1> we have
  <math|\<eta\><rsub|i*k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>=\<xi\><rsub|i*k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>=0>.
  We may thus write

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|R<rsub|k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>=R<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>+<big|sum><rsub|i=k><rsup|n-1>\<eta\><rsub|i*k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*i>+<big|sum><rsub|i=k><rsup|n-1>\<xi\><rsub|i*k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*i+1><eq-number>>>>>
  </align>

  Next consider <math|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>-\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+2>>.
  This has degree at most <math|2*n+D> and is orthogonal to
  <math|<with|math-font|cal*|P><rsub|2*k-2><rsup|\<bbb-C\>>>. Then
  <math|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>-\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+2>-<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>|)>*R<rsub|k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>>
  has degree at most <math|2*n+D> and is in the kernel of
  <math|\<beta\><rsub|j>> for all <math|j=1,\<ldots\>,D-1>. It is thus a
  linear combination of <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*k-2>>, <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>>
  and <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>>. We thus find

  <\equation>
    <\eqsplit>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>>|<cell|=\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+2>+<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>|)>*R<rsub|k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>+a<rsub|k>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>+b<rsub|k>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>+c<rsub|k>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k-2>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|=\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+2>+a<rsub|k>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>+b<rsub|k>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>+c<rsub|k>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k-2>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>+<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>|)>*R<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>+<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>|)>*<big|sum><rsub|i=k><rsup|n-1>\<eta\><rsub|i*k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*i>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>+<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>|)>*<big|sum><rsub|i=k><rsup|n-1>\<xi\><rsub|i*k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*i+1>.>>>>
    </eqsplit>
  </equation>

  These coefficients <math|a<rsub|k>>, <math|b<rsub|k>> and <math|c<rsub|k>>
  are unique as can be seen from the formulć

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|a<rsub|k>>|<cell|=-<frac|\<gamma\>*D|h<rsub|k>>*<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>x*P<rsub|2*k>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>*e<rsup|-2*V>*<space|0.17em>d*x-<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>|)>*\<xi\><rsup|<around|(|j|)>><rsub|k*k>,>>|<row|<cell|b<rsub|k>>|<cell|=<frac|\<gamma\>*D|h<rsub|k>>*<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>x*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>*P<rsub|2*k+1>*e<rsup|-2*V>*<space|0.17em>d*x-<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>|)>*\<eta\><rsup|<around|(|j|)>><rsub|k*k>,>>|<row|<cell|c<rsub|k>>|<cell|=-<frac|h<rsub|k>|h<rsub|k-1>>.>>>>
  </align*>

  Similarly <math|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>-\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>>
  has degree at most <math|2*n+D-1> and is orthogonal to
  <math|<with|math-font|cal*|P><rsub|2*k-1><rsup|\<bbb-C\>>>. Thus
  <math|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>-\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>-<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>|)>*R<rsub|k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>>
  is in the kernel of all <math|\<beta\><rsub|j>> and is orthogonal to
  <math|<with|math-font|cal*|P><rsub|2*k-1><rsup|\<bbb-C\>>>. Thus it must be
  proportional to <math|\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>>. This gives

  <\equation>
    <label|formula>

    <\eqsplit>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>>|<cell|=\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>+<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>|)>*R<rsub|k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>+<wide|a|~><rsub|k>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|=\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>+<wide|a|~><rsub|k>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>+<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>|)>*R<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>+<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>|)>*<big|sum><rsub|i=k><rsup|n-1>\<eta\><rsub|i*k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*i>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>+<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>|)>*<big|sum><rsub|i=k><rsup|n-1>\<xi\><rsub|i*k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*i+1>>>>>
    </eqsplit>
  </equation>

  As before <math|<wide|a|~><rsub|k>> is unique and may be written

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<wide|a|~><rsub|k>>|<cell|=<frac|\<gamma\>*D|h<rsub|k>>*<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>x*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>*P<rsub|2*k+1>*e<rsup|-2*V>*<space|0.17em>d*x-<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>|)>*\<eta\><rsup|<around|(|j|)>><rsub|k*k>>>>>
  </align*>

  (<reference|formula>) also implies the intriguing identity,

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|2=-<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>|)>*\<xi\><rsub|k*k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>><eq-number><label|intriguing>>>>>
  </align>

  These formulć imply <enquote|dual> formulć for <math|P<rsub|2*k>> and
  <math|P<rsub|2*k+1>>. Let us begin with the even case.
  <math|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*P<rsub|2*k>> is monic of degree <math|2*k+1>.
  Thus consider <math|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*P<rsub|2*k>-P<rsub|2*k+1>>
  which has degree at most <math|2*k>. Thus we may expand

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*P<rsub|2*k>-P<rsub|2*k+1>=<big|sum><rsub|m=0><rsup|k>\<mu\><rsub|m*k>*P<rsub|2*m>+<big|sum><rsub|m=0><rsup|k-1>\<lambda\><rsub|m*k>*P<rsub|2*m+1><eq-number>>>>>
  </align>

  We then find

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|\<mu\><rsub|m*k>>|<cell|=-<frac|\<gamma\>*D|h<rsub|m>>*<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>x*P<rsub|2*k>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*m+1>*e<rsup|-2*V>*<space|0.17em>d*x=<frac|h<rsub|k>|h<rsub|m>>*<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*m+1>|)>*\<xi\><rsub|k*m><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>+a<rsub|k>*\<delta\><rsub|k*m>>>|<row|<cell|\<lambda\><rsub|m*k>>|<cell|=<frac|\<gamma\>*D|h<rsub|m>>*<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>x*P<rsub|2*k>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*m>*e<rsup|-2*V>*<space|0.17em>d*x=-<frac|h<rsub|k>|h<rsub|m>>*<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*m>|)>*\<xi\><rsub|k*m><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>>>>>
  </align*>

  Finally, consider <math|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*P<rsub|2*k+1>-P<rsub|2*k+2>>.
  This has degree at most <math|2*k+1> and so may be expanded as follows.

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*P<rsub|2*k+1>-P<rsub|2*k+2>=<big|sum><rsub|m=0><rsup|k><wide|\<mu\>|~><rsub|m*k>*P<rsub|2*m>+<big|sum><rsub|m=0><rsup|k><wide|\<lambda\>|~><rsub|m*k>*P<rsub|2*m+1><eq-number>>>>>
  </align>

  Then after a calculation we find

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<wide|\<mu\>|~><rsub|m*k>>|<cell|=\<delta\><rsub|k,m+1>*c<rsub|k>-<frac|h<rsub|k>|h<rsub|m>>*<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*m+1>|)>*\<eta\><rsub|k*m><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>-b<rsub|k>*\<delta\><rsub|k*m>>>|<row|<cell|<wide|\<lambda\>|~><rsub|m*k>>|<cell|=<frac|h<rsub|k>|h<rsub|m>>*<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*m>|)>*\<eta\><rsub|k*m><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>+<wide|a|~><rsub|k>*\<delta\><rsub|k*m>>>>>
  </align*>

  Let us now derive a Christoffel-Darboux type formula for the pre-kernel
  (<reference|prekernel>). Note that the pre-kernel may be written

  <\equation*>
    S<rsub|n><around|(|x,y|)>=-<frac|1|2>*\<gamma\>*D*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>-V<around|(|y|)>>*<big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n-1><frac|P<rsub|2*k><around|(|x|)>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1><around|(|y|)>-P<rsub|2*k+1><around|(|x|)>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k><around|(|y|)>|h<rsub|k>>
  </equation*>

  Then applying our recursion formulć we find

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around|(|x-y|)>*S<rsub|n><around|(|x,y|)>=-<frac|1|2>*\<gamma\>*D*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>-V<around|(|y|)>>*<big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n-1><around*|(|<Circled|1><rsub|k>-<Circled|2><rsub|k>-<Circled|3><rsub|k>+<Circled|4><rsub|k>|)>>>>>
  </align*>

  where

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<Circled|1><rsub|k>>|<cell|=h<rsub|k><rsup|-1>*<around*|(|P<rsub|2*k+1><around|(|x|)>+<big|sum><rsub|m=0><rsup|k>\<mu\><rsub|m*k>*P<rsub|2*m><around|(|x|)>+<big|sum><rsub|m=0><rsup|k-1>\<lambda\><rsub|m*k>*P<rsub|2*m+1><around|(|x|)>|)>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1><around|(|y|)>>>|<row|<cell|<Circled|2><rsub|k>>|<cell|=h<rsub|k><rsup|-1>*P<rsub|2*k><around|(|x|)>*<around*|(|<big|sum><rsub|i=k><rsup|n-1><big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>|)>*<around*|[|\<eta\><rsub|i*k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*i><around|(|y|)>+\<xi\><rsub|i*k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*i+1><around|(|y|)>|]>|\<nobracket\>>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<around*|\<nobracket\>|<space|1em>+\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+2><around|(|y|)>+a<rsub|k>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1><around|(|y|)>+b<rsub|k>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k><around|(|y|)>+c<rsub|k>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k-2><around|(|y|)>+<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>|)>*R<rsup|<around|(|j|)>><rsub|n><around|(|y|)>|)>>>|<row|<cell|<Circled|3><rsub|k>>|<cell|=h<rsub|k><rsup|-1>*<around*|(|P<rsub|2*k+2><around|(|x|)>+<big|sum><rsub|m=0><rsup|k><wide|\<mu\>|~><rsub|m*k>*P<rsub|2*m><around|(|x|)>+<big|sum><rsub|m=0><rsup|k><wide|\<lambda\>|~><rsub|m*k>*P<rsub|2*m+1><around|(|x|)>|)>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k><around|(|y|)>>>|<row|<cell|<Circled|4><rsub|k>>|<cell|=h<rsub|k><rsup|-1>*P<rsub|2*k+1><around|(|x|)>*<around*|(|\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1><around|(|y|)>+<wide|a|~><rsub|k>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k><around|(|y|)>+<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>|)>*R<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|j|)>><around|(|y|)>|\<nobracket\>>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<around*|\<nobracket\>|<space|1em>+<big|sum><rsub|i=k><rsup|n-1><big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>|)>*<around*|[|\<eta\><rsub|i*k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*i><around|(|y|)>+\<xi\><rsub|i*k><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*i+1><around|(|y|)>|]>|)>>>>>
  </align*>

  Let us then write

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n-1><Circled|2><rsub|k>>|<cell|=h<rsub|n-1><rsup|-1>*P<rsub|2*n-2><around|(|x|)>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n><around|(|y|)>+h<rsub|n-1><rsup|-1>*P<rsub|2*n><around|(|x|)>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n-2><around|(|y|)>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>+<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1><big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>|)>*h<rsub|k><rsup|-1>*P<rsub|2*k><around|(|x|)>*R<rsup|<around|(|j|)>><rsub|n><around|(|y|)>+<big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n-1><Circled|5><rsub|k>>>>>
  </align*>

  where

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<Circled|5><rsub|k>>|<cell|=h<rsub|k-1><rsup|-1>*P<rsub|2*k-2><around|(|x|)>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k><around|(|y|)>+h<rsub|k><rsup|-1>*P<rsub|2*k><around|(|x|)>*<around*|(|a<rsub|k>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1><around|(|y|)>+b<rsub|k>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k><around|(|y|)>|)>-h<rsub|k><rsup|-1>*P<rsub|2*k+2><around|(|x|)>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k><around|(|y|)>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>+<big|sum><rsub|m=0><rsup|k>h<rsub|m><rsup|-1>*P<rsub|2*m><around|(|x|)>*<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*m+1>|)>*<around*|[|\<eta\><rsub|k*m><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k><around|(|y|)>+\<xi\><rsub|k*m><rsup|<around|(|j|)>>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1><around|(|y|)>|]>>>>>
  </align*>

  and similarly we may write

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n-1><Circled|4><rsub|k>>|<cell|=<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1><big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n-1>h<rsub|k><rsup|-1>*P<rsub|2*k+1><around|(|x|)>*\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>|)>*R<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|j|)>><around|(|y|)>+<big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n-1><Circled|6><rsub|k>>>>>
  </align*>

  where

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<Circled|6><rsub|k>>|<cell|=h<rsub|k><rsup|-1>*P<rsub|2*k+1><around|(|x|)>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1><around|(|y|)>+<wide|a|~><rsub|k>*h<rsub|k><rsup|-1>*P<rsub|2*k+1><around|(|x|)>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k><around|(|y|)>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>+<big|sum><rsub|m=0><rsup|k>h<rsub|m><rsup|-1>*P<rsub|2*m+1><around|(|x|)>*<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1>\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*m>|)>*<around*|[|\<eta\><rsup|<around|(|j|)>><rsub|k*m>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k><around|(|y|)>+\<xi\><rsup|<around|(|j|)>><rsub|k*m>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1><around|(|y|)>|]>>>>>
  </align*>

  Thus

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around|(|x-y|)>*S<rsub|n><around|(|x,y|)>>|<cell|=<frac|\<gamma\>*D|2>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>-V<around|(|y|)>>*<around*|(|h<rsub|n-1><rsup|-1>*P<rsub|2*n-2><around|(|x|)>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n><around|(|y|)>+h<rsub|n-1><rsup|-1>*P<rsub|2*n><around|(|x|)>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n-2><around|(|y|)>|\<nobracket\>>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<around*|\<nobracket\>|<space|1em>+<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1><big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n-1>h<rsub|k><rsup|-1>*<around*|[|\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>|)>*P<rsub|2*k><around|(|x|)>-\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>|)>*P<rsub|2*k+1><around|(|x|)>|]>*R<rsup|<around|(|j|)>><rsub|n><around|(|y|)>|)>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>+<frac|\<gamma\>*D|2>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>-V<around|(|y|)>>*<big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n-1><around*|(|-<Circled|1><rsub|k>+<Circled|5><rsub|k>+<Circled|3><rsub|k>-<Circled|6><rsub|k>|)>>>>>
  </align*>

  The reader may verify that a miraculous cancellation occurs so that
  <math|-<Circled|1><rsub|k>+<Circled|5><rsub|k>+<Circled|3><rsub|k>-<Circled|6><rsub|k>=0>.
  Finally using our solutions of <math|A<rsub|n>> and
  <math|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>>

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around|(|x-y|)>*S<rsub|n><around|(|x,y|)>>|<cell|=<frac|\<gamma\>*D|2>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>-V<around|(|y|)>>*<around*|(|h<rsub|n-1><rsup|-1>*P<rsub|2*n-2><around|(|x|)>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n><around|(|y|)>+h<rsub|n-1><rsup|-1>*P<rsub|2*n><around|(|x|)>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*n-2><around|(|y|)>|\<nobracket\>>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<around*|\<nobracket\>|<space|1em>+<big|sum><rsub|j=1><rsup|D-1><big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n-1>h<rsub|k><rsup|-1>*<around*|[|\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k+1>|)>*P<rsub|2*k><around|(|x|)>-\<beta\><rsub|j>*<around|(|<with|math-font|cal*|X>*\<Psi\><rsub|2*k>|)>*P<rsub|2*k+1><around|(|x|)>|]>*R<rsup|<around|(|j|)>><rsub|n><around|(|y|)>|)>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|=-<frac|e<rsup|-V<around|(|x|)>-V<around|(|y|)>>|4*\<pi\>*i>*<around*|(|A<rsup|-1><rsub|n><around|(|x|)>*A<rsub|n><around|(|y|)>|)><rsub|21>>>>>
  </align*>

  <\remark>
    We refer to this cancellation as <enquote|miraculous,> however one could
    have predicted that some sort of cancellation must occur simply from the
    form of the pre-kernel (<reference|prekernel>). Introduce the integral
    operator <math|\<bbb-S\><rsub|n>:L<rsup|2><around|(|\<bbb-R\>|)>\<to\>L<rsup|2><around|(|\<bbb-R\>|)>>
    which acts by

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around|(|\<bbb-S\><rsub|n>*\<psi\>|)><around|(|x|)>=<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>S<rsub|n><around|(|x,y|)>*\<psi\><around|(|y|)>*<space|0.17em>d*y>|<cell|>|<cell|\<psi\>\<in\>L<rsup|2><around|(|\<bbb-R\>|)>>>>>
    </align*>

    It is then easily seen that if <math|<around|{|H<rsub|k>|}><rsub|k\<in\>\<bbb-N\>>>
    is the sequence of <with|font-shape|italic|orthogonal> polynomials with
    respect to the weight <math|w=e<rsup|-2*V>>, then
    <math|\<bbb-S\><rsub|n>*<around|(|H<rsub|k>*e<rsup|-V>|)>=<frac|1|2>*H<rsub|k>*e<rsup|-V>>
    for <math|k\<leq\>2*n-1> and <math|\<bbb-S\><rsub|n>*<around|(|H<rsub|k>*e<rsup|-V>|)>=0>
    for <math|k\<geq\>2*n+D-1>. It thus follows that

    <\equation*>
      \<bbb-S\><rsub|n>=<frac|1|2>*\<bbb-K\><rsub|n>+<big|sum><rsub|j=2*n><rsup|2*n+D-2><frac|1|\<nu\><rsub|j>>*\<bbb-S\><rsub|n>*<around|(|H<rsub|j>*e<rsup|-V>|)>\<otimes\>H<rsub|j>*e<rsup|-V>
    </equation*>

    where <math|\<bbb-K\><rsub|n>=<big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n-1><frac|1|\<nu\><rsub|k>>*H<rsub|k>\<otimes\>H<rsub|k>>
    for <math|\<nu\><rsub|k>=<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>H<rsub|k><rsup|2>*e<rsup|-2*V>*<space|0.17em>d*x>.
    By the classical Christoffel-Darboux formula for orthogonal polynomials
    it follows that <math|<around|(|x-y|)>*S<rsub|n><around|(|x,y|)>> has
    rank at most <math|D+1>. Indeed, this is one of the ideas behind Widom's
    method.
  </remark>

  <section|A dynamical system><label|dynamicsection>

  Our Riemann-Hilbert problems can be used to yield an analogue of the Toda
  lattice for skew-orthogonal polynomials of symplectic type. We introduce a
  <math|t\<in\>\<bbb-R\>> dependence into the potential as

  <\equation>
    <label|deformation>V<around|(|z,t|)>\<assign\>V<rsub|0><around|(|z|)>+t*z
  </equation>

  Let <math|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^><around|(|z,t|)>> have the expansion

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^><around|(|z,t|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|=<around*|(|\<bbb-I\>+z<rsup|-1>*A<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|t|)>+z<rsup|-2>*A<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|t|)>+\<cal-O\><around|(|z<rsup|-3>|)>|)><around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|z<rsup|-2*n-D+1>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|z<rsup|2*n>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|z>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|\<ddots\>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|z>>>>>|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|<around|(|z\<to\>\<infty\>|)>>>>>
  </align*>

  Strictly speaking we should write <math|<wide|A|^><rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>>
  and <math|<wide|A|^><rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>> to emphasise that these
  matrices come from the expansion of <math|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>> rather than
  <math|A<rsub|n>> however we shall not do this to reduce notational clutter.
  Introduce the variables <math|a<rsub|i*j><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n,t|)>\<assign\>A<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|t|)><rsub|i*j>>
  and <math|a<rsub|i*j><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n,t|)>\<assign\>A<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|t|)><rsub|i*j>>
  for <math|i,j=1,\<ldots\>,D+1>. In what follows we shall often not write
  the dependence on <math|t> since this is always understood. Furthermore,
  introduce the variable

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|b<rsub|j><around|(|n|)>\<assign\><big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|k*j><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|j=3,\<ldots\>,D+1<eq-number><label|defb>>>>>
  </align>

  <\theorem>
    <label|skewtoda>The matrix elements <math|a<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|22>>,
    <math|a<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|2*i>>,
    <math|a<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|i*2>>,
    <math|a<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|22>>,
    <math|a<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|12>>,
    <math|a<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|i*2>> and <math|b<rsub|i>>, for
    <math|i=3,\<ldots\>,D+1>, satisfy the following first order dynamical
    system (<math|n\<geq\>0>, <math|t\<in\>\<bbb-R\>>).

    <\allowdisplaybreaks>
      <\align*>
        <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<frac|d*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>|d*t>>|<cell|=<big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|k*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|<frac|d*a<rsub|2*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>|d*t>>|<cell|=b<rsub|i><around|(|n|)>>|<cell|i=3,\<ldots\>,D+1>>|<row|<cell|<frac|d*a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>|d*t>>|<cell|=a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>-a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>>|<cell|i=3,\<ldots\>,D+1>>|<row|<cell|<frac|d*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>|d*t>>|<cell|=<big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|k*2><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|<frac|d|d*t>*ln
        a<rsub|12><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>>|<cell|=2*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>-<big|sum><rsub|j=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*j><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|j*2><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|<frac|d|d*t>*a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>>|<cell|=a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>+a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>>|<cell|i=3,\<ldots\>,D+1>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>+a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>-a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>+a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+2|)>*<frac|a<rsub|12><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>|a<rsub|12><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+2|)>>-a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)><rsup|2>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>-a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*<big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|k*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>>|<cell|>>>>
      </align*>
    </allowdisplaybreaks>

    \ and for <math|n\<geq\>1> and <math|t\<in\>\<bbb-R\>>,

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<frac|d*b<rsub|i><around|(|n|)>|d*t>>|<cell|=<frac|a<rsub|12><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>|a<rsub|12><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>>*a<rsub|2*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n-1|)>+a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|2*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>>|<cell|i=3,\<ldots\>,D+1>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>+a<rsub|2*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>-a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*a<rsub|2*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>+a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|2*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>-a<rsub|2*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)><around*|(|a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>|)><rsup|2>-a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*b<rsub|i><around|(|n|)>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>-2*a<rsub|2*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*<big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|k*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>+a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*b<rsub|i><around|(|n|)>>|<cell|>>>>
    </align*>

    Note that <math|a<rsub|12><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>\<neq\>0>
    so the above is well defined. The above dynamics are furthermore
    constrained by the relation

    <\align>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<big|sum><rsub|j=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*j><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|j*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>>|<cell|=2<eq-number><label|identity>>>>>
    </align>

    Our <enquote|initial data> with respect to <math|n> must satisfy
    <math|a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|0,t|)>=a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|0,t|)>=a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|0,t|)>=a<rsub|12><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|0,t|)>=a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|0,t|)>=b<rsub|i>*<around|(|0,t|)>=0>
    for <math|i\<geq\>3>.
  </theorem>

  The identity (<reference|identity>) may be seen as analogous to
  (<reference|intriguing>).

  <\remark>
    Note that repeated differentiation of (<reference|identity>) yields an
    infinite number of identities, so that the <math|k>th derivative of
    (<reference|identity>) yields an identity involving matrix elements at
    <math|k> different values of <math|n>.
  </remark>

  <\remark>
    Some of the matrix elements not included in Theorem <reference|skewtoda>
    may be related to those included by the following identities.

    <\align>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|a<rsub|i*1><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>>|<cell|=a<rsub|21><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|i=3,\<ldots\>,D+1<eq-number><label|deduce1>>>|<row|<cell|a<rsub|1*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>>|<cell|=a<rsub|12><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*a<rsub|2*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|i=3,\<ldots\>,D+1<eq-number><label|deduce2>>>|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|=a<rsub|21><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|12><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|<eq-number>>>|<row|<cell|0>|<cell|=a<rsub|12><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>=a<rsub|21><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>=a<rsub|i*j><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|i=1,\<ldots\>,D+1,<space|0.17em>j=3,\<ldots\>,D+1<eq-number>>>>>
    </align>

    These identities can be seen directly from the solution, though
    (<reference|deduce1>) and (<reference|deduce2>) we will deduce in the
    course of proving Theorem <reference|skewtoda>. The matrix elements
    <math|a<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|i*1>> for <math|i\<neq\>2> are left
    undetermined by these relations. Furthermore
    <math|a<rsub|i*j><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n,t|)>>, for
    <math|i,j\<geq\>3> do not enter into the dynamical system on their own
    but only in the combination of the variable
    <math|b<rsub|i>*<around|(|n,t|)>> (<reference|defb>).
  </remark>

  <\exmp>
    <label|exactsolution>In the case <math|D=2> it is possible to give an
    exact solution. Without loss of generality (by shifting and rescaling)
    one can take <math|V<rsub|0><around|(|z|)>=<frac|1|2>*z<rsup|2>>. With
    this initial condition one finds the following.

    <\align*>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|A<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|t|)>>|<cell|=<around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|-t*<around|(|2*n+1|)>>|<cell|0>|<cell|<frac|2*\<pi\>*i*e<rsup|-<frac|1|2>*t<rsup|2>>|<sqrt|2>*<around*|(|n-<frac|1|2>|)>!>>>|<row|<cell|0>|<cell|2*n*t>|<cell|-<frac|e<rsup|<frac|1|2>*t<rsup|2>>*n!|<sqrt|2>>>>|<row|<cell|<frac|e<rsup|<frac|1|2>*t<rsup|2>>*2*<sqrt|2>*<around*|(|n+<frac|1|2>|)>!|2*\<pi\>*i>>|<cell|-<frac|2*<sqrt|2>*e<rsup|-<frac|1|2>*t<rsup|2>>|<around|(|n-1|)>!>>|<cell|t>>>>>|)>>>|<row|<cell|A<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|t|)>>|<cell|=<around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|\<ast\>>|<cell|-i*<sqrt|\<pi\>>*<frac|2<rsup|2*n>*e<rsup|-t<rsup|2>>|<around|(|2*n-1|)>!>>|<cell|0>>|<row|<cell|-<frac|<around|(|2*n+1|)>!<sqrt|\<pi\>>|2<rsup|2*n+1>>*<frac|e<rsup|t<rsup|2>>|2*\<pi\>*i>>|<cell|n*<around|(|2*n-1|)>*<around|(|t<rsup|2>-<frac|1|2>|)>+n>|<cell|0>>|<row|<cell|\<ast\>>|<cell|-<frac|2*<sqrt|2>*<around|(|2*n-1|)>*t*e<rsup|-<frac|1|2>*t<rsup|2>>|<around|(|n-1|)>!>>|<cell|0>>>>>|)>>>>>
    </align*>

    We find also <math|b<rsub|3>*<around|(|n,t|)>=-<frac|t*e<rsup|<frac|1|2>*t<rsup|2>>*n!|<sqrt|2>>>.
    The reader may verify that this is an exact solution of the dynamical
    system in Theorem <reference|skewtoda> for the case <math|D=2>.
  </exmp>

  Let us introduce the <math|<around|(|D+1|)>\<times\><around|(|D+1|)>>
  matrices

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|E<rsub|1>>|<cell|=<math-up|diag><around|(|1,<wide*|0,\<ldots\>,0|\<wide-underbrace\>><rsub|D<text|times>>|)>>>|<row|<cell|E<rsub|2>>|<cell|=<math-up|diag><around|(|0,1,<wide*|0,\<ldots\>,0|\<wide-underbrace\>><rsub|D-1<text|times>>|)>>>|<row|<cell|\<sigma\>>|<cell|=E<rsub|1>-E<rsub|2>>>>>
  </align*>

  Let us then define

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<widebreve>A<rsub|n>*<around|(|z,t|)>\<assign\><wide|A<rsub|n>|^><around|(|z,t|)>*<space|0.17em>e<rsup|V<around|(|z,t|)>*\<sigma\>><eq-number>>>>>
  </align>

  It is then easy to see that <math|<widebreve>A<rsub|n>> satisfies the
  following RHP.

  <\rhp>
    Let <math|\<Gamma\>> be as in (<reference|gamma>). Then
    <math|<widebreve>A<rsub|n>> has the following properties.

    <\enumerate>
      <item><math|z\<mapsto\><widebreve>A<rsub|n>*<around|(|z,t|)>> is an
      analytic function on <math|\<bbb-C\>\<setminus\>\<Gamma\>>.

      <item><math|z\<mapsto\><widebreve>A<rsub|n>*<around|(|z,t|)>> has
      continuous left (<math|+>) and right (<math|->) non-tangential boundary
      values <math|x\<mapsto\><widebreve>A<rsub|n><rsup|\<pm\>>*<around|(|x,t|)>>
      for <math|x\<in\>\<Gamma\>\<setminus\><around|{|0|}>> which are related
      by the jump condition

      <\align*>
        <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<widebreve>A<rsub|n><rsup|+>*<around|(|x,t|)>=<widebreve>A<rsub|n><rsup|->*<around|(|x,t|)><around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-lborder|0ln>|<cwith|1|-1|2|2|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|3|3|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|4|4|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|5|5|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|6|6|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|7|7|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|8|8|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|9|9|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|10|10|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|11|11|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|12|12|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|13|13|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|14|14|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|15|15|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|16|16|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|17|17|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|18|18|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|19|19|cell-halign|c>|<cwith|1|-1|19|19|cell-rborder|0ln>|<table|<row|<cell|1<space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em><space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em><space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em><space|0.17em>>|<cell|<space|0.17em>>>|<row|<cell|-\<chi\><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>>|<cell|1>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|-\<chi\><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|1>>>|<cell|>|<cell|1>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|\<vdots\>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|\<ddots\>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|-\<chi\><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|D-1>>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|1>>>>>|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|x\<in\>\<Gamma\>\<setminus\><around|{|0|}>>>>>
      </align*>

      <item>For each <math|t\<in\>\<bbb-R\>>, the function
      <math|z\<mapsto\><widebreve>A<rsub|n>*<around|(|z,t|)>> is bounded in a
      neighbourhood of <math|0\<in\>\<bbb-C\>>.

      <item>For each <math|t\<in\>\<bbb-R\>>,
      <math|z\<mapsto\><widebreve>A<rsub|n>*<around|(|z,t|)>> satisfies the
      normalisation

      <\align*>
        <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<widebreve>A<rsub|n>*<around|(|z,t|)>=<around*|(|\<bbb-I\>+\<cal-O\><around|(|z<rsup|-1>|)>|)><around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|z<rsup|-2*n-D+1>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|z<rsup|2*n>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|z>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|\<ddots\>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|z>>>>>|)>*e<rsup|V<around|(|z,t|)>*\<sigma\>>>|<cell|>|<cell|<around|(|z\<to\>\<infty\>|)>>>>>
      </align*>
    </enumerate>
  </rhp>

  Because the jump matrix is independent of both <math|n> and <math|t>,
  standard Riemann-Hilbert theory now enables us to derive a dynamical
  system. In particular <math|<widebreve>A<rsub|n+1>*<around|(|z,t|)>> and
  <math|<frac|\<partial\><widebreve>A<rsub|n>*<around|(|z,t|)>|\<partial\>*t>>
  both satisfy the first to third properties, differing only on the fourth
  property. Because of the continuity of the boundary values and boundedness
  at <math|0> we find that

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|z>|<cell|\<mapsto\><widebreve>A<rsub|n+1>*<around|(|z,t|)><widebreve>A<rsub|n>*<around|(|z,t|)><rsup|-1>>>|<row|<cell|z>|<cell|\<mapsto\><frac|\<partial\><widebreve>A<rsub|n>*<around|(|z,t|)>|\<partial\>*t><widebreve>A<rsub|n>*<around|(|z,t|)><rsup|-1>>>>>
  </align*>

  extend to entire functions on <math|\<bbb-C\>>. Let us write the asymptotic
  expansion (<math|z\<to\>\<infty\>>)

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<widebreve>A<rsub|n>*<around|(|z,t|)>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|=<around*|(|\<bbb-I\>+z<rsup|-1>*A<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|t|)>+z<rsup|-2>*A<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|t|)>+\<cal-O\><around|(|z<rsup|-3>|)>|)><around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|z<rsup|-2*n-D+1>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|z<rsup|2*n>>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|z>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|\<ddots\>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|>|<cell|z>>>>>|)>*e<rsup|V<around|(|z,t|)>*\<sigma\>>>>>>
  </align*>

  A short calculation yields the <with|font-shape|italic|Lax pair>,

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<widebreve>A<rsub|n+1>*<around|(|z,t|)>>|<cell|=<around*|(|z<rsup|2>*E<rsub|2>+z*\<rho\><rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|t|)>+\<rho\><rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|t|)>|)><widebreve>A<rsub|n>*<around|(|z,t|)><eq-number><label|Laxpair1>>>|<row|<cell|<frac|\<partial\><widebreve>A<rsub|n>*<around|(|z,t|)>|\<partial\>*t>>|<cell|=<around*|(|z*\<sigma\>+\<kappa\><rsub|n><around|(|t|)>|)><widebreve>A<rsub|n>*<around|(|z,t|)><eq-number><label|Laxpair2>>>>>
  </align>

  where

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|\<rho\><rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|t|)>>|<cell|=A<rsub|n+1><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|t|)>*E<rsub|2>-E<rsub|2>*A<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|t|)>>>|<row|<cell|\<rho\><rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|t|)>>|<cell|=\<bbb-I\>-E<rsub|1>-E<rsub|2>+A<rsub|n+1><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|t|)>*E<rsub|2>+E<rsub|2>*<around*|(|A<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|t|)><rsup|2>-A<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|t|)>|)>-A<rsub|n+1><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|t|)>*E<rsub|2>*A<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|t|)>>>|<row|<cell|\<kappa\><rsub|n><around|(|t|)>>|<cell|=<around|[|A<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|t|)>,\<sigma\>|]>>>>>
  </align*>

  <\remark>
    The reader will observe that the jump matrices of
    <math|<widebreve>A<rsub|n>> are not only independent of <math|n> and
    <math|t> but also independent of <math|z>. Thus one could also derive
    <math|<around|(|n,z|)>> and <math|<around|(|t,z|)>> Lax pairs. Indeed one
    could consider more general deformations than (<reference|deformation>).
  </remark>

  <\remark>
    [Analogue of Three Term Recurrence]<label|recurrence> We note that
    (<reference|Laxpair1>) implies a similar equation for
    <math|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>>, i.e.

    <\equation*>
      <wide|A<rsub|n+1>|^><around|(|z|)>=<around*|(|z<rsup|2>*E<rsub|2>+z*\<rho\><rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>+\<rho\><rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>|)><wide|A<rsub|n>|^><around|(|z|)>
    </equation*>

    Considering the second column of both sides yields a recursion relation,
    quadratic in <math|z>, which may be regarded as a <math|\<beta\>=4>
    analogue of the three term recurrence for orthogonal polynomials (recall
    equations (<reference|12Ahat>),(<reference|22Ahat>),(<reference|i2Ahat>)).
  </remark>

  Before proceeding we must indicate a point of rigour. To compute this Lax
  pair we have exchanged a <math|z\<to\>\<infty\>> limit with a derivative
  with respect to <math|t>. How can this be justified? The proof is somewhat
  tedious and so we only sketch how this is done. The solution of our even
  problem <math|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>> is expressible as rational combinations
  of integrals of the form <math|<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|j>>x<rsup|k>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x,t|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x>,
  <math|<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>>x<rsup|k>*e<rsup|-2*V<around|(|x,t|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x>,
  <math|<big|int><rsub|\<Gamma\><rsub|j>><frac|x<rsup|k>|x-z>*e<rsup|-V<around|(|x,t|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x>
  and <math|<big|int><rsub|\<bbb-R\>><frac|x<rsup|k>|x-z>*e<rsup|-2*V<around|(|x,t|)>>*<space|0.17em>d*x>.
  The proof reduces to showing that such integrals are
  <math|\<cal-C\><rsup|\<infty\>>> functions of <math|t> and that we can
  differentiate under the integral sign. Both can be justified by a dominated
  convergence argument. This implies that
  <math|A<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>> and
  <math|A<rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>> are
  <math|<with|math-font|cal*|C><rsup|\<infty\>>> functions of <math|t>.

  Moving forward, let us write

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|\<rho\><around|(|z,t,n|)>>|<cell|=z<rsup|2>*E<rsub|2>+z*\<rho\><rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|t|)>+\<rho\><rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|t|)>>>|<row|<cell|\<lambda\>*<around|(|z,t,n|)>>|<cell|=z*\<sigma\>+\<kappa\><rsub|n><around|(|t|)>>>>>
  </align*>

  Then the compatibility condition (or <with|font-shape|italic|zero curvature
  condition>) of the above Lax pair (<reference|Laxpair1> and
  <reference|Laxpair2>) is

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<frac|\<partial\>*\<rho\><around|(|z,t,n|)>|\<partial\>*t>+\<rho\><around|(|z,t,n|)>*\<lambda\>*<around|(|z,t,n|)>-\<lambda\>*<around|(|z,t,n+1|)>*\<rho\><around|(|z,t,n|)>=0>|<cell|>|<cell|\<forall\>z\<in\>\<bbb-C\><eq-number><label|compatibility>>>>>
  </align>

  The left hand side is at most a cubic polynomial in <math|z>, all of whose
  coefficients must vanish. In fact the coefficient of <math|z<rsup|3>> is
  <math|<around|[|E<rsub|2>,\<sigma\>|]>=0> which yields no information. The
  coefficient of <math|z<rsup|2>> yields the equation

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|E<rsub|2>*\<kappa\><rsub|n><around|(|t|)>-\<kappa\><rsub|n+1><around|(|t|)>*E<rsub|2>+<around|[|\<rho\><rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|t|)>,\<sigma\>|]>=0<eq-number>>>>>
  </align>

  However when we substitute in our formulć for
  <math|\<rho\><rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>> and <math|\<kappa\><rsub|n>> we
  find that the left hand side is identically zero. So the quadratic
  coefficient also yields no information. Thus the left hand side of
  (<reference|compatibility>) is in fact a linear polynomial in <math|z>.

  The coefficient of <math|z> in (<reference|compatibility>) yields

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<frac|d*\<rho\><rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|t|)>|d*t>+\<rho\><rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|t|)>*\<kappa\><rsub|n><around|(|t|)>-\<kappa\><rsub|n+1><around|(|t|)>*\<rho\><rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|t|)>+<around|[|\<rho\><rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|t|)>,\<sigma\>|]>=0<eq-number><label|linear>>>>>
  </align>

  while the constant term gives

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<frac|d*\<rho\><rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|t|)>|d*t>+\<rho\><rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|t|)>*\<kappa\><rsub|n><around|(|t|)>-\<kappa\><rsub|n+1><around|(|t|)>*\<rho\><rsub|n><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|t|)>=0<eq-number><label|constant>>>>>
  </align>

  (<reference|linear>), after substituting our expressions for
  <math|\<rho\><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n><around|(|t|)>> and
  <math|\<rho\><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n><around|(|t|)>>, yields

  <\equation>
    <label|linearexpansion>

    <\eqsplit>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|>|<cell|-A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2>+A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2>-E<rsub|1>*A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2>-E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n>+E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n>*E<rsub|2>-E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n>*E<rsub|1>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|+E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2>-E<rsub|2>*<frac|d*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>|d*t>-E<rsub|2><around|(|A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>|)><rsup|2>*E<rsub|2>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|-E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>*E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>+E<rsub|2><around|(|A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>|)><rsup|2>+<frac|d*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>|d*t>*E<rsub|2>+E<rsub|1><around|(|A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>|)><rsup|2>*E<rsub|2>=0>>>>
    </eqsplit>
  </equation>

  The <math|<around|(|1,1|)>> matrix element of (<reference|linearexpansion>)
  is <math|0>. The <math|<around|(|1,2|)>> matrix element yields the identity

  <\equation>
    <label|identity1>2*a<rsub|12><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>=<big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|1*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|k*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>
  </equation>

  The <math|<around|(|2,1|)>> matrix element yields

  <\equation>
    <label|identity2>2*a<rsub|21><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>=<big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|k*1><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>
  </equation>

  The <math|<around|(|2,2|)>> element gives that the quantity

  <\equation*>
    <around|(|n,t|)>\<mapsto\><frac|d|d*t>*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n,t|)>-<big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n,t|)>*a<rsub|k*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n,t|)>
  </equation*>

  is independent of <math|n>.

  <\lemma>
    <label|nequal0>

    <\equation*>
      <frac|d|d*t>*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>=<big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|k*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>
    </equation*>
  </lemma>

  <\proof>
    To show this we need only show that

    <\equation*>
      <frac|d|d*t>*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|0,t|)>-<big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|0,t|)>*a<rsub|k*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|0,t|)>=0
    </equation*>

    However when <math|n=0>, the <math|<around|(|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>|)><rsub|22>=P<rsub|2*n>=P<rsub|0>=1>,
    and hence <math|a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|0,t|)>=0>.
    Similarly <math|<around|(|<wide|A<rsub|n>|^>|)><rsub|k*2>=0> for
    <math|k\<geq\>3> and so <math|a<rsub|k*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|0,t|)>=0>.
  </proof>

  The <math|<around|(|1,i|)>> and <math|<around|(|i,1|)>> matrix elements for
  <math|i\<geq\>3> give <math|0>. The <math|<around|(|2,i|)>> matrix element
  for <math|i\<geq\>3> gives

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<frac|d*a<rsub|2*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>|d*t>=<big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|k*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|<around|(|i\<geq\>3|)>>>>>
  </align*>

  Finally the <math|<around|(|i,2|)>> matrix element (<math|i\<geq\>3>) gives
  the equation

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<frac|d*a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n,t|)>|d*t>=a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n,t|)>-a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n,t|)>*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n,t|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|<around|(|i\<geq\>3|)>>>>>
  </align*>

  Next let us move onto the constant term (<reference|constant>), which gives
  us the complicated expression,

  <\equation>
    <label|constant2>

    <\eqsplit>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em><space|1em>E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n>*E<rsub|1>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>-E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>*E<rsub|1>+E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>*E<rsub|2>-E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>*A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>+E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2>-E<rsub|2><around|(|A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>|)><rsup|3>*E<rsub|2>-A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>*E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>-A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>*E<rsub|2>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>+E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n>+E<rsub|1>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>*A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2>-A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2><around|(|A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>|)><rsup|2>*E<rsub|1>+E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>*<frac|d*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>|d*t>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>-E<rsub|1><around|(|A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>|)><rsup|2>*E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>-E<rsub|2>*<frac|d*A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n>|d*t>-E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2><around|(|A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>|)><rsup|2>-E<rsub|1>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>*E<rsub|1>+E<rsub|2>*<frac|d*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>|d*t>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>-A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2>*<frac|d*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>|d*t>+<frac|d*A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n+1>|d*t>*E<rsub|2>-E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>-E<rsub|2><around|(|A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>|)><rsup|2>*E<rsub|1>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>+E<rsub|2><around|(|A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>|)><rsup|2>*E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>+A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>+A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>*E<rsub|1>-A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>-A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>*E<rsub|2>+E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>*E<rsub|2>+E<rsub|2><around|(|A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>|)><rsup|2>*E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>-A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>-<frac|d*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>|d*t>*E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>+A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2>+E<rsub|2><around|(|A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>|)><rsup|3>*E<rsub|1>+E<rsub|1>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>+A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2><around|(|A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>|)><rsup|2>*E<rsub|2>+A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2><around|(|A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>|)><rsup|2>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>-E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n>*E<rsub|2>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n>-E<rsub|1>*A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|1>-A<rsup|<around|(|1|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|1>*A<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|n+1>*E<rsub|2>=0>>>>
    </eqsplit>
  </equation>

  The <math|<around|(|1,1|)>> matrix element of (<reference|constant2>) is
  <math|0>. The <math|<around|(|2,2|)>> matrix element yields, after some
  simplification, the relation

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<frac|d*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>|d*t>-<big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*a<rsub|k*2><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>=<frac|d*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>|d*t>-<big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|k*2><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>>>>>
  </align*>

  <\lemma>
    <\equation*>
      <frac|d*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>|d*t>=<big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|k*2><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>
    </equation*>
  </lemma>

  <\proof>
    Follows by the same observations as in Lemma <reference|nequal0>.
  </proof>

  The <math|<around|(|2,1|)>> matrix element of (<reference|constant2>) gives
  the following equation.

  <\equation>
    <label|constant21>2*<around|(|a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>-a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>|)>*a<rsub|21><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>+<frac|d|d*t>*a<rsub|21><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>+<big|sum><rsub|j=3><rsup|D+1>b<rsub|j><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|j*1><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>=0
  </equation>

  The <math|<around|(|1,2|)>> matrix element gives

  <\equation>
    <label|constant12><frac|d|d*t>*a<rsub|12><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>+<big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|1*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*a<rsub|k*2><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>-2*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|12><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>=0
  </equation>

  The <math|<around|(|i,1|)>> matrix element for <math|i\<geq\>3> gives

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|a<rsub|i*1><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>=a<rsub|21><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|<around|(|i\<geq\>3|)><eq-number><label|identity3>>>>>
  </align>

  The <math|<around|(|1,i|)>> matrix element gives

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|a<rsub|1*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>=a<rsub|12><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*a<rsub|2*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|<around|(|i\<geq\>3|)><eq-number><label|identity4>>>>>
  </align>

  The <math|<around|(|i,2|)>> matrix element yields after some simplification

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<frac|d|d*t>*a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>>|<cell|=a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>+a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>+a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>>|<cell|<around|(|i\<geq\>3|)>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>-a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>-a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*<big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|k*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>+a<rsub|21><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+2|)>*a<rsub|12><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>-a<rsub|i*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)><rsup|2>>|<cell|>>>>
  </align*>

  The <math|<around|(|2,i|)>> matrix element gives

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>-a<rsup|<around|(|2|)>><rsub|21><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|12><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|2*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n-1|)>-a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|2*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>-a<rsub|2*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|<around|(|i\<geq\>3|)>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>+a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>*a<rsub|2*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>+a<rsub|2*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)><around*|(|a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>|)><rsup|2>+2*a<rsub|2*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*<big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|k*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>>|<cell|>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>+<frac|d*b<rsub|i><around|(|n|)>|d*t>+<around|(|a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>-a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>|)>*b<rsub|i><around|(|n|)>-a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|2*i><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>=0>|<cell|>|<cell|>>>>
  </align*>

  Let us now combine our formulć. Substituting (<reference|identity3>) into
  (<reference|identity2>) we find

  <\equation>
    <big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|k*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>=2
  </equation>

  We would have found the same if we had substituted (<reference|identity4>)
  into (<reference|identity1>). Note that if we combine
  (<reference|constant21>) and (<reference|constant12>) we find

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<frac|d|d*t>*ln
    a<rsub|21><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>+<frac|d|d*t>*ln
    a<rsub|12><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>>|<cell|=2*a<rsub|22><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>-<big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>b<rsub|k><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|k*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>-<big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|k*2><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|=-<frac|d|d*t><wide*|<big|sum><rsub|k=3><rsup|D+1>a<rsub|2*k><rsup|<around|(|1|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|k*2><rsup|<around|(|1|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>|\<wide-underbrace\>><rsub|=2>=0>>>>
  </align*>

  which we already knew since <math|a<rsub|21><rsup|<around|(|2|)>><around|(|n|)>*a<rsub|12><rsup|<around|(|2|)>>*<around|(|n+1|)>=1>.
  Finally, the <math|<around|(|i,j|)>> matrix element of
  (<reference|constant2>) for <math|i,j\<geq\>3>, after substituting the
  identities we have derived so far, is identically zero so yields no further
  information. This completes the proof of Theorem
  <reference|skewtoda>.<new-page>

